n''' and was the first large temple to have been dedicated to Isis. In earlier shrines at the site, she may have been worshipped alongside her mythological husband, [[Osiris]], and son, [[Horus]]. It was begun by the [[pharaoh|kings]] of the [[Thirtieth Dynasty of Egypt|Thirtieth Dynasty]] (380\u2013343 BC) and completed under [[Ptolemy III]] (r. 246\u2013222 BC).<ref>Wilkinson, Richard H. (2003). ''The Complete Gods and Goddesses of Ancient Egypt''. Thames & Hudson. p. 149</ref>\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; border: none;\"\n|{{hiero|pr \u1e25bj(t)<ref name = Gauthier110>{{cite book |last1=Gauthier |first1=Henri |title=Dictionnaire des Noms G\u00e9ographiques Contenus dans les Textes Hi\u00e9roglyphiques Vol. 2 |date=1925 |pages=110-111 |url=https://archive.org/details/Gauthier1925_2/page/n57}}</ref>|<center><hiero>O1:Z1-W4-D58-M17*M17-O49</hiero></center>|align=center|era=3ip}}\n|{{hiero|\u1e25bj(t)<ref>{{cite book |last1=Wallis Budge |first1=E. A. |title=An Egyptian hieroglyphic dictionary: with an index of English words, king list and geological list with indexes, list of hieroglyphic characters, coptic and semitic alphabets, etc. Vol II |date=1920 |publisher=[[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]] |page=[https://archive.org/details/egyptianhierogly02budguoft/page/1021 1021] |url=https://archive.org/details/egyptianhierogly02budguoft}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Gauthier |first1=Henri |title=Dictionnaire des Noms G\u00e9ographiques Contenus dans les Textes Hi\u00e9roglyphiques Vol. 4 |date=1927 |page=24 |url=https://archive.org/details/Gauthier1927/page/n15/}}</ref>|<center><hiero>V28-D58-M17*M17-W4-X1:O49</hiero> '''or''' <hiero>V28-D58-W4-O49</hiero></center>|align=center|era=default}}\n|{{hiero|pr \u1e25bj<ref name = Gauthier110/>|<center><hiero>O1:Z1-W4-X1:O49</hiero></center>|align=center|era=pt}}\n|}\nThe Iseion became one of Isis's major [[cult (religious practice)|cult]] centers. It paralleled the deity's most important temple, located at [[Philae]] in [[Upper Egypt]].<ref name=\"Wilkinson 2000\"/> Most Egyptian temples were built primarily of [[limestone]] or [[sandstone]], with harder stones such as [[granite]] used only for individual elements such as statues, [[obelisks]], or doorways,<ref>Wilkinson, Richard H. (2000). ''The Complete Temples of Ancient Egypt''. Thames & Hudson. pp. 40\u201341</ref> but the Iseion was built entirely of granite.<ref name=\"Wilkinson 2000\"/> The temple was demolished at some point, possibly in ancient times, by an earthquake or by the removal of its stone to serve as building material. Only scattered blocks remain there today.<ref name=\"Wilkinson 2000\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Favard-Meeks, Christine (1991). ''Le temple de Behbeit el-Hagara. Essai de reconstitution et d'interpr\u00e9tation''. Buske Verlag.\n*Favard-Meeks, Christine (2016). [https://www.temple-behbeit.org/ Behbeit el-Hagara web site] \n==External links==\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n\n\n[[Category:Isis]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Nile Delta]]\n[[Category:Egyptian temples]]\n[[Category:Archaeological discoveries with year of discovery missing]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 3rd century BC]]\n[[Category:3rd-century BC establishments in Egypt]]\n[[Category:Thirtieth Dynasty of Egypt]]\n\n\n{{Egypt-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Village in Gharbia Governorate, Egypt}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name          = Behbeit El Hegara\n|other_name             = {{lang|ar|\u0628\u0647\u0628\u064a\u062a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u062c\u0627\u0631\u0629}}\n|native_name            = \n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        =\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = Behbeit