{"title_page": "The Washington Times", "text_new": "{{about|Established in 2015 to bring down  Trump! Some far left anti trump supporters might think Wikipedia is real news.... it\u2019s not! Any definition can be hacked. |the newspaper with a similar name published from 1894 to 1939|Washington Times (1894\u20131939)|the newspaper with a similar name published from 1939 to 1954|Washington Times-Herald}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|American conservative broadsheet newspaper published in Washington, D.C.}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| logo = The Washington Times (2019-10-31).svg\n| image = Washtimesfrontapril5.jpg\n| caption = Front page for August 22, 2016\n| type = [[Daily newspaper]]\n| format = [[Broadsheet]]\n| founder = [[Sun Myung Moon]]\n| publisher = Larry Beasley\n| editor = \n| president = \n| chiefeditor = Christopher Dolan\n| depeditor = \n| assoceditor = \n| maneditor = \n| newseditor = Victor Morton\n| managingeditordesign = Cathy Gainor\n| opeditor = Charles Hurt\n| sportseditor = David Eldridge\n| photoeditor = \n| staff = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1982|5|17}}\n| political = <!-- Do not fill in without establishing consensus on Talk page. -->\n| language = English\n| ceased publication = \n| relaunched = \n| headquarters = 3600 [[New York Avenue NE]]<br />[[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| circulation = 52,059 daily\n| circulation_date     = 2019\n| circulation_ref      = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://gotoanr.com/documents/database/district-of-columbia.pdf|title=District of Columbia Newspaper Circulation|website=ANR|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n| sister newspapers = \n| ISSN = 0732-8494\n| oclc = 8472624\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| free = \n| dirinteractive = \n| logo_size = \n| motto = ''Reliable Reporting. The Right Opinion.'' \n| logo_alt = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| owner = Operations Holdings (via The Washington Times, LLC)\n| generalmanager = David Dadisman<ref>http://twt-media.washtimes.com/media/misc/2016/05/26/RollingThunder_Final.pdf</ref>\n| metroeditor = \n| metrochief = \n| readership = \n| publishing_country = United States\n| publishing_city = Washington, D.C.\n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n'''''The Washington Times''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[daily newspaper]] published in [[Washington, D.C.]], that covers general interest topics with a particular emphasis on [[Politics of the United States|national politics]]. Its [[broadsheet]] daily edition is distributed throughout the [[District of Columbia]] and in parts of [[Maryland]] and [[Virginia]]. A weekly [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] edition aimed at a national audience is also published.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/subscribe/|title=Subscribe}}</ref>\n\n''The Washington Times'' was founded on May 17, 1982, by [[Unification movement]] leader [[Sun Myung Moon]] and owned until 2010 by [[News World Communications]], an international media [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] founded by Moon. It is currently owned by Operations Holdings, which is owned by the Unification movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/1d470c008efe41e2bd0777173c246f36/washington-times-reports-first-profitable-month|title=The Washington Times reports first profitable month|website=The Big Story|language=en-US|access-date=February 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.operationsholdings.com/about-us/|title=Operations Holdings INC \u2013 About Us|author=|date=|website=www.operationsholdings.com|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout its history, ''The Washington Times'' has been known for its [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] political stance.<ref name=\"Hall\" /><ref name=\"Glaberson\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" />  It has published many columns which reject the [[scientific consensus]]es on [[climate change]],<ref name=\"Playing Climate-Change Telephone\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/playing-climate-change-telephone|title=Playing Climate-Change Telephone|work=The New Yorker|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://climatefeedback.org/evaluation/tom-harris-deceptive-temperature-record-claims/|title=Analysis of \"Deceptive temperature record claims\"|date=August 28, 2015|work=Climate Feedback|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-mh-attack-on-climate-change-scientists-20151204-column.html|title=The attack on climate change scientists continues in Washington|last=Hiltzik|first=Michael|website=Los Angeles Times|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref> on [[ozone depletion]],<ref name=\"handful\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fpMh3nh3JI0C|title=Merchants of Doubt: How a Handful of Scientists Obscured the Truth on Issues from Tobacco Smoke to Global Warming|authors=Naomi Oreskes & Erik M. Conway|publisher=Bloomsbury|pages=130\u2013135|date=2010|isbn=9781608192939}}</ref> on the harmful effects of [[second-hand smoke]],<ref name=\"myths\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.org/news/article.asp?id=2715|title=Anthology of 1995's Environmental Myths|last=Singer|first=Fred|date=1995|work=The Washington Times|access-date=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181229193017/http://www.independent.org/news/article.asp?id=2715|url-status = dead|archive-date=2018-12-29}}</ref><ref name=\"inq climate\">{{Cite book|url=http://cup.columbia.edu/book/the-inquisition-of-climate-science/9780231157193|title=The Inquisition of Climate Science|last=Powell|first=James Lawrence|date=2011|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231527842|location=|pages=57, 198}}</ref>  and which have spread [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|misinformation regarding the 2019-2020 coronavirus outbreak]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Monitoring|first=B. B. C.|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037|title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online|date=2020-01-30|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> \nIt has drawn controversy for publishing [[racism|racist]] content, including commentary and [[conspiracy theories]] about [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]],<ref name=\"Obama\">\n* {{Cite news|author=Betsy Woodruff|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/cruzs-cozy-ties-to-dcs-most-prominent-paranoid-islamophobe|title=Cruz's Cozy Ties To DC's Most Prominent, Paranoid Islamophobe|newspaper=Daily Beast|date=December 15, 2015}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/12/08/meet-frank-gaffney-the-anti-muslim-gadfly-who-produced-donald-trumps-anti-muslim-poll/|title=Meet Frank Gaffney, the anti-Muslim gadfly reportedly advising Donald Trump's transition team|last=Bump|first=Philip|date=November 16, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}\n* {{Cite web|author=Eli Clifton|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/12/08/donald-trump-frank-gaffney-islamophobia-poll/|title=Meet Donald Trump's Islamophobia Expert|website=Foreign Policy|date=December 8, 2015}}\n* {{Cite web|author=Robert Schlesinger|url=https://www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/robert-schlesinger/2009/06/09/the-nutty-obama-is-a-muslim-charge-is-back-now-with-a-hitler-comparison|title=The Nutty 'Obama Is a Muslim' Charge Is Back (Now With a Hitler Comparison!)|work=U.S. News & World Report|date=June 9, 2009}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/brendan-nyhan/pundits-blame-the-victims_b_692327.html|title=Pundits Blame the Victims on Obama Muslim Myth|website=Huffington Post|date=August 24, 2010|author=Brendan Nyhan}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://archives.cjr.org/united_states_project/the_washington_times_takes_a_b.php|title=''The Washington Times'' takes a giant step\u2014backwards|last=Blake|first=Mariah|date=February 11, 2013|work=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=June 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref> supporting  [[neo-Confederate]] [[historical revisionism]],<ref name=\":7\"/> and promoting [[Islamophobia]].<ref name=\"deseretnews.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865656561/Report-says-list-of-6Islamophobic-groups7-reaches-new-high.html|title=Report says list of 'Islamophobic groups' reaches new high|date=June 20, 2016|website=Deseret News|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref> \n\n==History==\n\n===Beginnings===\n''The Washington Times'' was founded in 1982 by [[News World Communications]], an international media [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] associated with the [[Unification movement]] which also owns newspapers in [[South Korea]], [[Japan]], and [[South America]], as well as the [[news agency]] [[United Press International]] (UPI).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/18/us/around-the-nation-sun-myung-moon-paper-appears-in-washington.html |title=Sun Myung Moon Paper Appears in Washington |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 18, 1982}}</ref> [[Bo Hi Pak]], the chief aide of Unification movement founder and leader [[Sun Myung Moon]], was the founding president and the founding chairman of the board.<ref>Pak was founding president of The Washington Times Corporation (1982\u20131992), and founding chairman of the board. [[Bo Hi Pak]], Appendix B: Brief Chronology of the Life of Dr. Bo Hi Pak, in ''Messiah: My Testimony to Rev. Sun Myung Moon, Vol I'' by Bo Hi Pak (2000), Lanham, MD: University Press of America.</ref> Moon asked [[Richard L. Rubenstein]], a rabbi and college professor who had written on the [[Holocaust]], to serve on the board of directors.<ref>\"Rabbi Joins the Board of Moonie Newspaper\", ''[[The Palm Beach Post]]'', May 21, 1978</ref> ''The Washington Times''{{'}} first editor and publisher was [[James R. Whelan]].\n\nAt the time of founding of ''The Washington Times'', Washington had only one major newspaper, ''[[The Washington Post]]''. [[Massimo Introvigne]], in his 2000 book ''The Unification Church'', said that the ''Post'' had been \"the most anti-Unificationist paper in the United States.\"<ref>[http://www.signaturebooks.com/excerpts/unification.htm excerpt] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513174704/http://www.signaturebooks.com/excerpts/unification.htm |date=May 13, 2008 }} The Unification Church Studies in Contemporary Religion, Massimo Introvigne, 2000, Salt Lake City, Utah: Signature Books, {{ISBN|1-56085-145-7}} p. 25</ref> In 2002, at an event held to celebrate the ''Times''{{'}} 20th anniversary, Moon said: \"''The Washington Times'' is responsible to let the American people know about God\" and \"''The Washington Times'' will become the instrument in spreading the truth about God to the world.\"<ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/2002/05/23/moon-speech-raises-old-ghosts-as-the-times-turns-20/505334e8-8ce6-44eb-a767-ee7895107cae/|title=Moon Speech Raises Old Ghosts as the Times Turns 20|last=Ahrens|first=Frank|date=May 23, 2002|work=The Washington Post|via=|accessdate=August 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n''The Washington Times'' was founded the year after the ''[[Washington Star]]'', the previous \"second paper\" of D.C., went out of business. A large percentage of the staff came from the ''Star''. When it launched, it was unusual among American [[broadsheet]]s in publishing a full color front page, along with full color front pages in all its sections and color elements throughout. It also used ink that it advertised as being less likely to come off on the reader's hands than the type used by the ''Post''.<ref name=\"'70s 146\">{{cite book |title=How We Got Here: The '70s |last=Frum |first=David |authorlink=David Frum |year=2000 |publisher=Basic Books |location=New York City |isbn=978-0-465-04195-4 |page=[https://archive.org/details/howwegothere70sd00frum/page/146 146] |url=https://archive.org/details/howwegothere70sd00frum/page/146 |url-access=registration }}</ref> At its start, it had 125 reporters, 25 percent of whom were members of the [[Unification Church of the United States]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/cult/unification/wtimes.htm The Nation's Capital Gets A New Daily Newspaper],''[[The Washington Post]]'', May 17, 1982</ref>\n\nAfter a brief editorship under [[Smith Hempstone]], de Borchgrave (formerly of UPI and ''[[Newsweek]]'') was executive editor from 1985 to 1991.<ref name=Gamarekian>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/05/18/us/washington-times-editor-resigns-but-will-stay-on-to-write-articles.html|title=''Washington Times'' Editor Resigns, But Will Stay On to Write Articles|year=1991|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Barbara Gamarekian}}</ref> Borchgrave was credited for encouraging energetic reporting by staff, but was known to make unorthodox journalistic decisions. During his tenure, ''The Washington Times'' mounted a fundraising drive for [[Contras|Contra]] rebels in [[Nicaragua]] and offered rewards for information leading to the arrest of [[Nazi war criminals]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/17/business/media/arnaud-de-borchgrave-a-journalist-whose-life-was-a-tale-itself-dies-at-88.html|title=Arnaud de Borchgrave, Journalist Whose Life Was a Tale Itself, Dies at 88|last=Roberts|first=Sam|date=February 16, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>Emily Langer, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/arnaud-de-borchgrave-swashbuckling-newsweek-foreign-correspondent-dies/2015/02/15/52609204-b552-11e4-a200-c008a01a6692_story.html Arnaud de Borchgrave, swashbuckling Newsweek foreign correspondent, dies], ''The Washington Post'' (February 15, 2015).</ref>\n\n[[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] is said to have read ''The Washington Times'' every day during his presidency.<ref name=\"Behind the Times\">[http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=1569 Behind the Times] [[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]] August/September 1987</ref> In 1997 he said, \"The American people know the truth. You, my friends at ''The Washington Times'', have told it to them. It wasn't always the popular thing to do. But you were a loud and powerful voice. Like me, you arrived in Washington at the beginning of the most momentous decade of the century. Together, we rolled up our sleeves and got to work. And\u2014oh, yes\u2014we won the [[Cold War]].\"<ref name=\"Dear Leader's Paper Moon\">[http://prospect.org/article/dear-leaders-paper-moon Dear Leader's Paper Moon] [[The American Prospect]] September 19, 2005</ref>\n\n===Wesley Pruden editorship===\n[[Wesley Pruden|Wesley \"Wes\" Pruden]], previously a correspondent and then a [[managing editor]], was named executive editor in 1991.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=http://archives.cjr.org/year/95/2/times.asp|title=Washington's Other Paper|last=|first=|date=1995|work=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20040223081524/http://archives.cjr.org/year/95/2/times.asp|archive-date=February 23, 2004|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref> During his editorship, the paper took a strongly [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] and [[Nativism (politics)|nativist]] stance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cjr.org/united_states_project/the_washington_times_takes_a_b.php|title=The Washington Times takes a giant step\u2014backwards|website=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=March 11, 2016}}</ref>[[File:2008 07 The Washington Times newsroom 02.jpg|thumb|247x247px|''The Washington Times'' newsroom]]\n\nIn 1992, [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Il Sung]] gave his first and only interview with the Western news media to ''The Washington Times'' reporter [[Josette Sheeran]], who later became Executive Director of the [[United Nations World Food Programme]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/11/world/americas/11sheeran.html?pagewanted=all A Desire to Feed the World and Inspire Self-Sufficiency], ''New York Times'', August 11, 2007</ref> At the time, ''The Washington Times'' had one-eighth the circulation of the ''Post'' (100,000 compared to 800,000) and two-thirds of its subscribers subscribed to both papers.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1992/01/27/business/the-media-business-washington-times-moves-to-reinvent-itself.html Washington Times Moves to Reinvent Itself], Alex S. Jones, ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 27, 1992.</ref> In 1994 it introduced a weekly \"national edition\" which was published in a [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] format and distributed nationwide.<ref name=\"nyt1994\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/27/business/the-media-business-conservative-daily-tries-to-expand-national-niche.html?pagewanted=all Conservative Daily Tries to Expand National Niche], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 27, 1994</ref>\n\nU.S. President [[George H. W. Bush]] encouraged the political influence of ''The Washington Times'' and other Unification movement activism in support of American [[foreign policy]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Goodman |first=Walter |date=January 21, 1992 |title=Review/Television; Sun Myung Moon Changes Robes |periodical=New York Times |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CEEDB1F3FF932A15752C0A964958260&sec=&spon=}}</ref> In 1997, the ''[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]],'' which is critical of U.S. and [[Israel]]i policies, praised ''The Washington Times'' and its sister publication, ''[[News World Communications|The Middle East Times]]'', for what it called their objective and informative coverage of [[Islam]] and the [[Middle East]], while criticizing their generally pro-Israel editorial policy. The ''Report'' suggested that these newspapers, being owned by religious institutions, were less influenced by pro-Israel pressure groups in the U.S.<ref>[http://www.wrmea.com/backissues/1297/9712060.html As U.S. Media Ownership Shrinks, Who Covers Islam?] {{webarchive |url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20050421165328/http://www.wrmea.com/backissues/1297/9712060.html |date=April 21, 2005 }}, ''[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]]'', December 1997</ref>\n\nIn 2004, ''Post'' columnist [[David Ignatius]] reported that [[Chung Hwan Kwak]], a top leader of the Unification movement, wanted ''The Washington Times'' to \"support international organizations such as the [[United Nations]] and to campaign for world peace and interfaith understanding.\" This, Ignatius wrote, created difficulties for Pruden and some of the ''Times''{{'}} columnists. Ignatius also mentioned the Unification movement's reconciliatory attitude towards North Korea, which at the time included joint business ventures, and Kwak's advocacy for greater understanding between the U.S. and the [[Islamic world]] as issues of contention. Ignatius predicted that conservatives in Congress and the [[George W. Bush]] administration would support Pruden's position over Kwak's.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A50909-2004Jun17.html Tension of the Times] ''[[The Washington Post]]'' June 18, 2004, \"Insiders say the church's new line is that with the end of the Cold War, it's important to support international organizations such as the United Nations and to campaign for world peace and interfaith understanding. That stance would be awkward for ''The Washington Times''{{'}}s hard-line editor in chief, Wesley Pruden, and its stable of neoconservative columnists.\"</ref>\n\n===John Solomon editorship===\n[[File:2008 09 The Washington Times - Printing and Distribution Center.jpg|thumb|The printing and distribution center of ''The Washington Times'']]\nIn January 2008, Pruden retired and [[John F. Solomon]] began as executive editor. Solomon had previously worked for the [[Associated Press]], and had most recently been head of [[investigative reporting]] and mixed media development at the ''Post''.<ref>[http://www.connpost.com/ci_8089629?source=rss State Native to lead DC newspaper] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211111011/http://www.connpost.com/ci_8089629?source=rss |date=February 11, 2009 }} ''[[Connecticut Post]]'' January 26, 2008</ref><ref>[http://biz.yahoo.com/nytimes/080211/1194745974399.html?.v=4 Ex-''Washington Post'' Reporter to Lead a Rival] ''[[The New York Times]]'' February 11, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Erik Wemple|url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/display.php?id=34649|title=Playing Center: John Solomon is pushing evenhandedness at ''The Washington Times''|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301235126/http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/display.php?id=34649 |archive-date=March 1, 2008 |work=[[Washington City Paper]]|date=February 29, 2008}}</ref> Within a month, ''The Washington Times'' changed some of its [[style guide]] to conform more to what was becoming mainstream media usage. It announced that it would no longer use words like \"[[illegal immigration|illegal aliens]]\" and \"[[homosexuality|homosexual]]\", and in most cases opt for \"more neutral terminology\" like \"illegal immigrants\" and \"gay,\" respectively. It also decided to stop using \"Hillary\" when referring to [[United States Senator|Senator]] [[Hillary Clinton]], and the word \"marriage\" in the expression \"[[gay marriage]]\" would no longer appear in quotes in the newspaper. These changes in policy drew criticism from some conservatives.<ref name=salonfeb>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/politics/war_room/2008/02/26/washington_times/index.html |title=''Washington Times'' updates style guide, conservatives up in arms |work=Salon |date=February 27, 2008 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'' magazine attributed the ''Times''{{'}} apparent political moderation to differences of opinion over the UN and North Korea, and said: \"The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] right may be losing its most devoted media ally.\"<ref>[http://www.prospect-magazine.co.uk/article_details.php?id=7720 News and Curiosities], ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'', September 2006</ref>[[File:Washington Times dispenser.jpg|thumb|200px|''Times'' dispenser]]\n\nIn July 2010, the Unification Church issued a letter protesting the direction ''The Washington Times'' was taking and urging closer ties with it.<ref>[http://www.poynter.org/column.asp?id=45&aid=187388 Unification Church CEO, others respond to unsigned blog post about ''Washington Times''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724054956/http://www.poynter.org/column.asp?id=45&aid=187388 |date=July 24, 2010 }}, Poynter Online (website of the [[Poynter Institute]]), July 22, 2010</ref> In August 2010, a deal was made to sell it to a group more closely related to the movement. [[Editor-in-chief]] [[Sam Dealey]] said that this was a welcome development among the ''Times''{{'}} staff.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/25/business/media/25times.html?_r=1&dbk Deal in Works for ''The Washington Times''], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 25, 2010</ref> In November 2010, Moon and a group of former editors purchased ''The Washington Times'' from News World Communications for $1. This ended a conflict within the Moon family that had been threatening to shut down the paper completely.<ref>{{cite news |title=Moon group buys back ''Washington Times'' |work=The Washington Post |date=November 3, 2010 |page=C1 |first=Ian |last=Shapira}}</ref>  In June 2011, Ed Kelley, formerly of ''[[The Oklahoman]]'', was hired as editor overseeing both news and opinion content.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/washington-times-names-ed-kelley-as-editor-will-oversee-news-coverage-and-opinion-content/2011/06/10/AGP2gqOH_story.html ''Washington Times'' names Ed Kelley as editor; will oversee news coverage and opinion content], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', June 10, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Douglas D. M. Joo stepped down as senior executive, president, and chairman.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Longtime Times executive Joo resigns, takes job in Korea|url = http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/oct/14/longtime-times-executive-joo-resigns/|work= The Washington Times|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref> ''Times'' president Tom McDevitt took his place as chairman, and Larry Beasley was hired as the company's new president and [[chief executive officer]].<ref>{{Cite news|title = New Times CEO moves quickly to name leadership team, set path to profitability|url = http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/oct/16/new-times-ceo-moves-quickly-name-leadership-team-s/?page=1|work= The Washington Times|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref>  In 2013, it worked with Herring Networks to create a new conservative cable news channel, [[One America News]], which began broadcasting in mid\u20112013.<ref>{{cite news |title=''The Washington Times'' extending reach with cable network |first=Jennifer |last=Harper |url=http://m.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/mar/13/the-washington-times-extending-reach-cable-network/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=March 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}<br />{{cite news |title=One America News Network, New Conservative Cable Channel, Sets Launch |first=David |last=Freedlander |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/03/14/one-america-news-network-new-conservative-cable-channel-sets-launch.html |newspaper=Daily Beast |date=March 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}<br />{{cite news |title=Herring Plans to Launch New Conservative News Network |first=Keach |last=Hagey |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324392804578358743706989224 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=March 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013  ''The Washington Times'' hired [[David Keene]], the former president of the [[National Rifle Association]] and [[American Conservative Union]] chairman, to serve as its opinion editor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/07/david-keene-exnra-president-named-washington-times-168277.html|title=David Keene, ex-NRA president, named Washington Times opinion editor|last=Byers|first=Dylan|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=December 26, 2018}}</ref> Around the same time, Solomon returned as editor and also served as vice president of content and business development.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Solomon returns to lead content, business strategies at ''The Washington Times''|url = http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/jul/8/solomon-returns-lead-content-business-strategies-w/?page=1|access-date = February 7, 2016|work= The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jimromenesko.com/2013/07/08/john-solomon-returns-to-the-washington-times/|title=John Solomon returns to ''The Washington Times''|website=JIMROMENESKO.COM|access-date=April 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423010844/http://jimromenesko.com/2013/07/08/john-solomon-returns-to-the-washington-times/|archive-date=April 23, 2016|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref>  Solomon's tenure was marked by a focus on profitability. He left for [[Circa News]] in December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/12/07/john-solomon-leaves-washington-times-joins-circa-re-launch/|title=John Solomon leaves Washington Times, joins Circa re-launch|last=Wemple|first=Erik|date=December 7, 2015|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Finances===\nIn 1991, Moon said he had spent between $900 million and $1 billion on ''The Washington Times''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unification.net/1991/911223.html|title=Reverend Sun Myung Moon Speaks on Our Mission During the Time of World Transition|author=Damian Anderson|date=December 23, 1991|publisher=Unification.net|accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> By 2002, Moon had spent between $1.7 billion and $2 billion according to different estimates.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn?pagename=article&contentId=A60061-2002May22 |work=The Washington Post |title=Moon Speech Raises Old Ghosts as the Times Turns 20 |first=Frank |last=Ahrens |date=May 23, 2002 |accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"wash-chinni.asp2\" />  In November 2009, ''The New York Times'' reported that ''The Washington Times'' would no longer be receiving funds from the Unification movement and might have to cease publication or become an [[online publication]] only.<ref name=\"nyt1212009\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/01/business/media/01moon.html With Tumult at the Top, ''Washington Times'' Faces Uncertainty], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 30, 2009.</ref> Later that year, it fired 40 percent of its 370 employees and stopped its subscription service, instead distributing the paper free in some areas of Washington including branches of the government. A subscription website owned by the paper, theconservatives.com, continued, as did the ''Times''{{'}} three-hour [[radio program]], ''America's Morning News''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/03/business/media/03paper.html Large Staff Cuts Announced at ''The Washington Times''], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 2, 2009</ref> The paper announced that it would cease publication of its Sunday edition, along with other changes, partly in order to end its reliance on subsidies from the Unification movement.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20190305144454/http://www.editorandpublisher.com/eandp/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1004054777 ''Washington Times'' Dropping Sunday Edition As Part of 'Refocused' Approach], ''[[Editor & Publisher]]'', December 21, 2009</ref> On December 31, 2009, ''The Washington Times'' announced that it would no longer be a full-service newspaper, eliminating its metropolitan-news and sports sections.<ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/local/ap/washington-times-cuts-sports-section-others-80415182.html ''Washington Times'' cuts sports section, others]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''[[Washington Examiner]]'', December 31, 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/jan/01/daly-the-end-of-times/?page=2 Eulogy for sports], ''The Washington Times'', January 3, 2010</ref>  In March 2011, it announced that some former staffers would be rehired and that the paper would bring back its sports, metro, and life sections.<ref>[http://www.politico.com/blogs/onmedia/0311/Washington_Times_relaunching_Monday.html ''Washington Times'' relaunching Monday], [[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]], March 16, 2011</ref>  It had its first profitable month in September 2015, ending the streak of losses in the paper's first 33 years.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jennifer Harper|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/oct/14/washington-times-reaches-profitability-after-33-ye/?page=1|title=''Washington Times'' reaches profitability after 33 years, $1 billion in losses|work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n\n==Political stance, content and controversies==\n''The Washington Times'' holds a [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] political stance.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite news |last=Hall |first=Mimi |title=Bush, aides boost access of conservative media |work=USA Today |date=March 22, 2001|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/politics/2001-03-22-media.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"Glaberson\">{{cite news |last=Glaberson |first=William |title=Conservative Daily Tries to Expand National Niche |work=The New York Times |date=June 27, 1994|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/27/business/the-media-business-conservative-daily-tries-to-expand-national-niche.html |accessdate=July 25, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/03/27/media/seth-rich-brother-sues-washington-times/index.html|title=Seth Rich's brother sues right-wing activists, ''Washington Times'' over conspiracy theories|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|work=CNNMoney|access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.palgrave.com/gp/book/9783319711102|title=Islam, Securitization, and US Foreign Policy {{!}} Erdoan A. Shipoli {{!}} Palgrave Macmillan|last=|first=|year=|isbn=|location=|page=247|language=en}}</ref> ''[[The Columbia Journalism Review]]'' wrote in 1995, that the paper \"is like no major city daily in America in the way that it wears its political heart on its sleeve. No major paper in America would dare be so partisan.\"<ref name=\":18\" /> The ''Post'' reported in 2002, that it \"was established by Moon to [[Anti-communism|combat communism]] and be a conservative alternative to what he perceived as the [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] leanings of ''The Washington Post''. Since then, the paper has fought to prove its editorial independence, trying to demonstrate that it is neither a \"Moonie paper\" nor a booster of the political right but rather a fair and balanced reporter of the news.\"<ref name=\"Washington Post\" /> ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' reported in 2007 that it had become \"essential reading for political news junkies\" soon after its founding, and described the paper as a \"conservative newspaper with close ties to every Republican administration since Reagan.\"<ref>[https://www.motherjones.com/washington_dispatch/2007/04/bush_moon.html Bush Sr. To Celebrate Rev. Sun Myung Moon\u2014Again] ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' April 29, 2007</ref>\n\nIn a ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'' essay in 2008, American historian<ref>{{Cite web|title=Bill Moyers Journal. Bill Moyers interviews Thomas Frank |publisher=PBS|url=https://www.pbs.org/moyers/journal/08012008/profile3.html|access-date=February 6, 2016}}</ref> [[Thomas Frank]] linked ''The Washington Times'' to the modern American conservative movement, saying, \"There is even a daily newspaper\u2014''The Washington Times''\u2014published strictly for the movement's benefit, a [[propaganda]] sheet whose distortions are so obvious and so alien that it puts one in mind of those official party organs one encounters when traveling in [[authoritarianism|authoritarian]] countries.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.harpers.org/archive/2008/08/0082132|title=x|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' noted in 2009 that it had been \"a crucial training ground for many rising conservative journalists and a must-read for those in the movement. A veritable who's who of conservatives\u2014[[Tony Blankley]], [[Frank J. Gaffney Jr.]], [[Larry Kudlow]], [[John Podhoretz]] and [[Tony Snow]]\u2014has churned out copy for its pages.\"<ref name=\"nyt1212009\" /> ''The Columbia Journalism Review'' noted that reporters for the ''Times'' had used it as a springboard to other mainstream news outlets.<ref name=\"wash-chinni.asp2\">[http://www.cjr.org/issues/2002/5/wash-chinni.asp Washington 2002: The Other Paper] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419012416/http://www.cjr.org/issues/2002/5/wash-chinni.asp|date=April 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, ''Post'' veteran [[Ben Bradlee]] said, \"I see them get some local stories that I think the ''Post'' doesn't have and should have had.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjr.org/issues/2002/5/wash-stability.asp|title=Washington 2002: Donald Graham's ''Washington Post''|author=|date=November 24, 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031124234138/http://www.cjr.org/issues/2002/5/wash-stability.asp|archivedate=November 24, 2003|url-status = dead|accessdate=March 19, 2018|df=}}</ref> In January 2011, conservative commentator [[Paul Weyrich]] said, \"''The Washington Post'' became very arrogant and they just decided that they would determine what was news and what wasn't news and they wouldn't cover a lot of things that went on. And ''The Washington Times'' has forced the ''Post'' to cover a lot of things that they wouldn't cover if the ''Times'' wasn't in existence.\"<ref>[http://www.mediachannel.org/originals/moontranscript.shtml MediaChannel.org \u2013 Frontline: Reverend Moon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107074820/http://www.mediachannel.org/originals/moontranscript.shtml|date=January 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOpinion editor [[Charles Hurt]] was one of [[Donald Trump]]'s earliest supporters in Washington.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/07/the-trump-show-214075|title=The Trump Dynasty Takes Over the GOP|last=|first=|date=|website=politico.com|access-date= May 3, 2017}}</ref> In 2018 he included Trump with Ronald Reagan, Martin Luther King, [[Margaret Thatcher]], and [[Pope]] [[John Paul II]] as \"great champions of freedom.\"<ref>The Corrosion of Conservatism: Why I Left the Right, [[Max Boot]], Liveright Publishing, October 9, 2018, page 124</ref>\n\n=== Science coverage ===\n==== Climate change denial ====\n''The Washington Times'' is known for promoting [[climate change denial]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCright|first=Aaron M.|last2=Dunlap|first2=Riley E.|date=August 18, 2011|title=Organized Climate Change Denial|url=http://www.oxfordhandbooks.com/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199566600.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199566600-e-10|journal=The Oxford Handbook of Climate Change and Society|language=en|volume=|pages=152|doi=10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199566600.003.0010|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"Playing Climate-Change Telephone\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> [[Michael E. Mann]], director of the Earth System Science Center at [[Pennsylvania State University]], characterizes the ''Times'' as a prominent outlet that propagates \"climate change disinformation.\"<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|url=http://cup.columbia.edu/book/the-hockey-stick-and-the-climate-wars/9780231152549|title=The Hockey Stick and the Climate Wars: Dispatches from the Front Lines|last=Mann|first=Michael E.|date=March 2012|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231526388|location=|pages=64}}</ref> [[Naomi Oreskes]], Professor of the History of Science at [[Harvard University]], and [[Erik M. Conway]], historian of science at [[NASA]]'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory at the [[California Institute of Technology]], wrote in their 2010 book ''[[Merchants of Doubt]]'' that the ''Times'' has given the public a false sense that the science of anthropogenic climate change was in dispute by giving disproportionate coverage of fringe viewpoints and by preventing scientists from rebutting coverage in the ''Times''.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite journal|last=Kitcher|first=Philip|date=June 4, 2010|title=The Climate Change Debates|journal=Science|language=en|volume=328|issue=5983|pages=1230\u20131234|doi=10.1126/science.1189312|issn=1095-9203|bibcode=2010Sci...328.1230K|doi-access=free}}</ref> For example, the paper reprinted a column by [[Steve Milloy]] criticizing research of [[climate change in the Arctic]], without disclosing Milloy's financial ties to the [[fossil fuel]] industry.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Naomi Oreskes & Erik M. Conway|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fpMh3nh3JI0C|title=Merchants of Doubt: How a Handful of Scientists Obscured the Truth on Issues from Tobacco Smoke to Global Warming|date=2010|publisher=Bloomsbury|page=247|isbn=9781608192939}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Climatic Research Unit email controversy]] (also known as \"Climategate\") in 2009 in the lead-up to the [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference|UN Climate Change Conference in Copenhagen]], the ''Times'' wrote in an editorial \"these revelations of fudged science should have a cooling effect on global-warming hysteria and the panicked policies that are being pushed forward to address the unproven theory.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shorensteincenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/d72_mayer.pdf|title=Stories of Climate Change: Competing Narratives, the Media, and U.S. Public Opinion 2001-2010|last=Mayer|first=Frederick|date=2012|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Eight committees investigated the controversy, and found no evidence of fraud or scientific misconduct. In 2010, the ''Times'' published an article claiming that February 2010 snow storms \"Undermin[e] The Case For Global Warming One Flake At A Time\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/02/09/washington-times-february_n_455199.html|title=Washington Times: February Snow Storms \"Undermin[e] The Case For Global Warming One Flake At A Time\"|last=|first=|date=2010|newspaper=The Huffington Post|access-date=}}</ref> A 2014 ''Times'' editorial mocked the \"global warming scam\" and asserted, \"The planetary thermometer hasn\u2019t budged in 15 years. Wildfires, tornadoes, hurricanes and other \u2018extreme\u2019 weather events are at normal or below-normal levels. Pacific islands aren't submerged. There's so much ice the polar bears are celebrating.\"<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|last=Corneliussen|first=Steven Corneliussen Steven T.|date=July 1, 2014|title=News dispatches from the climate wars|journal=Physics Today|language=EN|doi=10.1063/PT.5.8054}}</ref> The ''Times'' cited a blog post in support of these claims; ''[[PolitiFact]]'' fact-checked the claims in the blog post and concluded it was \"pants-on-fire\" false.<ref name=\":19\" /> The ''Times'' later said that a NASA scientist claimed that global warming was on a \"hiatus\" and that NASA had found evidence of [[global cooling]]; Rebecca Leber of ''[[The New Republic]]'' said that the NASA scientist in question said the opposite of what the ''Times'' claimed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/119033/conservatives-misrepresent-climate-scientist|title=The Right-Wing Press' New Climate Change Lie|work=The New Republic|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015, it published a column by [[Member of Congress|Congressman]] [[Lamar Smith]] in which he argued that the work of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] was \"not good science, [but] science fiction.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 1993, ''The Washington Times'' published articles purporting to debunk climate change.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/14/science/scientists-confront-renewed-backlash-on-global-warming.html|title=Scientists Confront Renewed Backlash on Global Warming|last=Stevens|first=William K.|date=September 14, 1993|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 28, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It headlined its story about the [[1997 Kyoto Protocol]] on climate change, \"Under the deal, the use of coal, oil and other fossil fuel in the United States would be cut by more than one-third by 2002, resulting in lower standards of living for consumers and a long-term reduction in economic growth.\"<ref name=\":822\">{{Cite web|url=https://global.oup.com/ushe/product/reporting-from-washington-9780195308921|title=Reporting from Washington|last=Ritchie|first=Donald|date=|website=|publisher=Oxford University Press|pages=262\u2013263|language=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Ozone depletion denial====\nIn the 1990s, ''The Washington Times'' published columns which cast doubt on the scientific consensus on the causes of [[ozone depletion]] (which had led to an \"ozone hole\"). It published columns disputing the science as late as 2000.<ref name=\"handful\"/> In 1991, NASA scientists warned of the potential of a major Arctic ozone hole developing in the spring of 1992 due to elevated levels of [[chlorine monoxide]] in the Arctic [[stratosphere]]. However, as the Arctic winter was unusually warm, the chemical reactions needed for ozone depletion did not occur. Even though the science was not incorrect, the ''Times''', along with other conservative media, subsequently created a \"[[The boy who cried wolf|crying wolf]]\" narrative where scientists were portrayed as political activists who were following an environmental agenda rather than the science. In 1992, it published an editorial saying, \"This is not the disinterested, objective, just-the-facts tone one ordinarily expects from scientists... This is the cry of the apocalyptic, laying the groundwork for a decidedly non-scientific end: public policy... it would be nice if the next time NASA cries 'wolf,' fewer journalists, politicians and citizens heed the warning like sheep.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|date=February 1, 2013|title=Climate change prediction: Erring on the side of least drama?|url= |journal=Global Environmental Change|language=en|volume=23|issue=1|pages=327\u2013337|doi=10.1016/j.gloenvcha.2012.10.008|issn=0959-3780|last1=Brysse|first1=Keynyn|last2=Oreskes|first2=Naomi|last3=o'Reilly|first3=Jessica|last4=Oppenheimer|first4=Michael}}</ref>\n\n==== Second-hand smoke denial====\nIn 1995, ''The Washington Times'' published a column by [[Fred Singer]], who is known for promoting views contrary to mainstream science on a number of issues, where Singer referred to the science on the adverse health impact of [[second-hand smoke]] as the \"second-hand smoke scare\", and accused the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] of distorting data when it classified second-hand smoke as harmful.<ref name=\"myths\"/><ref name=\"inq climate\"/> In 1995 it published an editorial titled \"How not to spend science dollars\" condemning a grant to the National Cancer Institute to study how political contributions from tobacco companies shape policy-making and the voting behavior of politicians.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Landman|first=Anne|last2=Glantz|first2=Stanton A.|date=2009|title=Tobacco Industry Efforts to Undermine Policy-Relevant Research|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=99|issue=1|pages=45\u201358|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2007.130740|issn=0090-0036|pmc=2600597|pmid=19008508}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.industrydocumentslibrary.ucsf.edu/tobacco/docs/#id=xkyk0101|title=How not to spend science dollars|last=|first=|date=1995|work=The Washington Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n====Misreporting on the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic====\nIn January 2020, ''The Washington Times'' published two widely shared articles about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] that suggested that the virus was created by China as a [[biological weapon]]. The article quotes a former Israeli intelligence officer as a source, but offered no evidence to support its claims. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Monitoring|first=B. B. C.|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037|title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online|date=2020-01-30|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== White nationalism, neo-Confederatism, racism, and Islamophobia ===\nUnder Pruden's editorship (1992\u20132008), ''The Washington Times'' regularly printed excerpts from racist hard-right publications including ''[[VDARE]]'' and ''[[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]]'', and [[Bill White (neo-Nazi)|Bill White]], leader of the American [[National Socialism|National Socialist]] Workers' Party, in its Culture Briefs section.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Robert Stacy McCain]], a member of the [[neo-Confederate]] white-supremacist group [[League of the South]], was hired and promoted to edit the Culture Briefs section, which became, according to [[Max Blumenthal]], \"a bulletin board for the racialist far right.\" Blumenthal also wrote that ''The Washington Times'' was \"characterized by extreme racial animus and connections to nativist and neo-Confederate organizations... from its earliest days the ''Times'' has been a hothouse for hard-line racialists and neo-Confederates.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/hell-times/|title=Hell of a Times|work=The Nation|last=Blumenthal|first=Max|date=September 20, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/palins-noxious-ghostwriter|title=Palin's Noxious Ghostwriter|last=Blumenthal|first=Max|date=November 16, 2009|work=The Daily Beast}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2013 article, the ''Columbia Journalism Review'' reported that under Pruden's editorship ''The Washington Times'' was \"a forum for the racialist hard right, including [[white nationalism|white nationalists]], neo-Confederates, and anti-immigrant scare mongers.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Between 1998 and 2004, the ''Times'' covered every biennial American Renaissance conference, hosted by the [[white supremacy|white supremacist]] [[New Century Foundation]]. According to the ''Columbia Journalism Review'', \"the paper's coverage of these events\u2014which are hotbeds for [[Holocaust denial|holocaust deniers]], [[neo-Nazi]]s, and [[eugenics|eugenicists]]\u2014was stunningly one sided\", and favorably depicted the conference and attendees.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2009, journalist [[David Neiwert]] wrote that it championed \"various white-nationalist causes emanating from the neo-Confederate movement (with which, until a recent housecleaning, two senior editors had long associations.)\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RdlqCwAAQBAJ|title=Eliminationists: How Hate Talk Radicalized the American Right|last=Neiwert|first=David|date=2009|publisher=Paradigm Publishers|edition=2016 Routledge|page=80|isbn=9781317260615}}</ref>\n\nA page in ''The Washington Times''{{'}} Sunday edition was devoted to the [[American Civil War]]. The [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]] was described with admiration several times in the article.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|author=Moe Tkacik|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/news/article/13039788/just-like-old-times-at-the-washington-times|title=Just Like Old Times at ''The Washington Times''?|work=Washington City Paper|date=November 5, 2010}}</ref> In 1993, Pruden gave an interview to the neo-Confederate magazine ''[[Southern Partisan]]'' where he said, \"Every year I make sure that we have a story in the paper about any [[Robert E. Lee Day|observance of Robert E. Lee's birthday]].\"<ref name=\":7\" /> Pruden said, \"And the fact that it falls around [[Martin Luther King]]\u2019s birthday,\" to which a ''Southern Partisan'' interviewer interjected, \"Makes it all the better,\" with Pruden finishing, \"I make sure we have a story. Oh, yes.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n''The Washington Times'' employed [[Samuel T. Francis]], a white nationalist, as a columnist and editor, beginning in 1991 after he was chosen by [[Pat Buchanan]] to take over his column.<ref name=\":9\">Heidi Berich and Kevin Hicks, \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=M7p6TDR1zwcC White Nationalism in America]\" in ''Hate Crimes'' (ed. Barbara Perr: Praeger, 2009), pp. 112\u201313.</ref>''<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2016/aug/16/secret-history-trumpism-donald-trump|title=The dark history of Donald Trump's rightwing revolt|last=Shenk|first=Timothy|date=August 16, 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Fascism: Post-war fascisms|last=Griffin|first=Roger|last2=Feldman|first2=Matthew|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=155}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/9781134201570/chapters/10.4324/9780203402191-10|chapter=The American Radical Right: The 1990s and Beyond|last=Potok|first=Mark|title=Western Democracies and the New Extreme Right Challenge|editor1=Roger Eatwell |editor2=Cas Mudde|page=59|publisher=Routledge|date=2003|doi=10.4324/9780203402191|isbn=9780203402191}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dnrkXM1C-eIC|title=Habits of Whiteness: A Pragmatist Reconstruction|last=MacMullan|first=Terrance|date=2009|publisher=Indiana University Press|page=147|isbn=978-0253002884}}</ref> In 1995, Francis resigned or was forced out after [[Dinesh D'Souza]] reported on racist comments that Francis made at a conference hosted by ''American Renaissance'' the previous year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncpress.org/book/9780807849606/the-rebuke-of-history|title=The Rebuke of History: The Southern Agrarians and American Conservative Thought|last=Murphy|first=Paul V.|date=2003|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|page=247}}</ref>''<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\"Kurtz\">[[Howard Kurtz]], [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1995/10/19/washington-times-clips-its-right-wing/dd009c93-883b-446c-bbbf-94c0a0570a1a/ Washington Times Clips Its Right Wing], ''The Washington Post'', October 19, 1995.</ref>''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/23/us/politics-on-the-move-buchanan-drawing-extremist-support-and-problems-too.html|title=Buchanan Drawing Extremist Support, and Problems, Too|last=Frantz|first=Douglas|date=February 23, 1996|work=The New York Times|last2=Janofsky|first2=Michael}}</ref> At the conference, Francis called on whites to \"reassert our identity and our solidarity, and we must do so in explicitly racial terms through the articulation of a racial consciousness as whites... The civilization that we as whites created in Europe and America could not have developed apart from the genetic endowments of the creating people.\"''<ref name=\"Kurtz\" />'' When Francis died in 2005, ''The Washington Times'' wrote a \"glowing\" [[obituary]] that omitted his racist beliefs, as well as his firing from the paper, and described him as a \"scholarly, challenging and sometimes pungent writer\"; in response, editor David Mastio of the conservative ''[[Washington Examiner]]'' wrote in an obituary that \"Sam Francis was merely a racist and doesn\u2019t deserve to be remembered as anything less.\"<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/shots-fired-book-delayed/|title=Shots Fired, Book Delayed|work=AdWeek|date=August 28, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dcexaminer.com/articles/2005/02/22/opinion/op-ed/01agoped.txt|title=Francis re-fought immoral battles of 1964|last=Mastio|first=David|work=Washington Examiner|date=February 22, 2005|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181226023344/http://calledasseen.blogspot.com/2005/02/washington-examiner-op-ed-on-sam.html|archive-date=December 26, 2018|access-date=December 26, 2018|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref> Mastio added that Francis \"led a double life {{ndash}} by day he served up conservative, red meat that was strong but never quite out of bounds by mainstream standards; by night, unbeknownst to the ''Times'' or his syndicate, he pushed white supremacist ideas.\"<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":17\" />\n\nThe [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC) noted that ''The Washington Times'' had by 2005 published at least 35 articles by Marian Kester Coombs, who was married to managing editor Francis Coombs. She had a record of racially incendiary rhetoric and had written for the white nationalist magazine ''[[The Occidental Quarterly|Occidental Quarterly]]''.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2005/washington-times-editor-and-wife-promote-radical-right-agenda|title=Washington Times Editor and Wife Promote Radical Right Agenda|magazine=Intelligence Report|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|authors=Heidi Beirich & Mark Potok|issue=Spring 2005|date=April 28, 2005}}</ref> The SPLC highlighted columns written by Marian Kester Coombs in ''The Washington Times'', in which she asserted that the whole of human history was \"the struggle of ... races\"; that non-white immigration is the \"importing [of] poverty and revolution\" that will end in \"the eventual loss of sovereign American territory\"; and that Muslims in England \"are turning life in this once pleasant land into a misery for its native inhabitants.\"<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nIn 2006, Moon's son [[Hyun Jin Moon]], president and CEO of News World Communications, dismissed managing editor Francis \"Fran\" Coombs because of accusations of racist editorializing. Coombs had made some racist and [[sexism|sexist]] comments, for which he was sued by his colleagues.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/hell-times/ |title=Hell of a Times |journal=The Nation |accessdate=July 1, 2013|date=September 21, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==== Coverage of Barack Obama ====\n\nIn 2008, ''The Washington Times'' published a column by Frank Gaffney that promoted the false [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories which asserted that President Barack Obama was born in Kenya]] and was courting the \"jihadist vote.\" Gaffney also published pieces in 2009 and 2010 promoting the false assertion that [[Barack Obama religion conspiracy theories|Obama is a Muslim]].<ref name=\"Obama\"/> In a 2009 column entitled \"'Inner Muslim' at work in Cairo\", Pruden wrote that President Obama was the \"first president without an instinctive appreciation of the culture, history, tradition, common law and literature whence America sprang. The genetic imprint writ large in his 43 predecessors is missing from the Obama DNA.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> In another 2009 column, Pruden wrote that Obama had \"no natural instinct or blood impulse\u201d for what America was about because he was \u201csired by a [[Kenya]]n father\u201d and \u201cborn to a mother attracted to men of the [[Third World]].\"<ref name=\":4\" /> These columns stirred controversy, leading the paper to assign David Mastio, by then the paper's deputy editor, to edit Pruden's work.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRock musician [[Ted Nugent]], a fervent critic of President Obama, published weekly columns for ''The Washington Times'' between 2010 and 2012.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2014/02/ted-nugent-loses-the-washington-times-rick-perry-rand-paul.html|title=Ted Nugent Loses the Washington Times, Rick Perry, Rand Paul|last=Weigel|first=David|date=February 21, 2014|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/06/ted-nugent-obama-humanity_n_1747876.html|title=Ted Nugent: 'Obama Represents Everything Bad About Humanity'|last=Gentilviso|first=Chris|date=August 6, 2012|work=Huffington Post|access-date=December 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/post/washington-times-and-its-columnist-ted-nugent/2012/04/18/gIQAPXJKRT_blog.html|title=Washington Times and its columnist, Ted Nugent|last=Wemple|first=Erik|date=2012|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> Prior to joining the ''Times'', Nugent stirred controversy by referring to Obama as a \"piece of shit\" and calling on him \"to suck on my machine gun\",<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2012/04/18/ted-nugents-greatest-hits-his-10-most-outlandish-quotes/|title=Ted Nugent's Greatest Hits|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref> and had also pleaded fealty to the [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|Confederate flag]].<ref name=\":13\" /> In 2012, Nugent was visited by the Secret Service after he alluded to beheading President Obama.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ted-nugent-confederacy-won-civil-war-john-roberts-346041|title=Ted Nugent Wonders if 'We'd Have Been Better Off if the South Had Won the Civil War'|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/19/ted-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-said|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910234929/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/19/ted-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-saided-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-said.html?source=dictionary|title=Nugent: President Obama Is 'Subhuman Mongrel'|last=Jacobs|first=Ben|date=February 19, 2014|work=The Daily Beast|language=en|archive-date=2015-09-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> He said that if Obama would win re-election, \"I will either be dead or in jail by this time next year.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7.com/archive/8625185/|title=Ted Nugent to be probed for anti-Obama rant?|last=Heller|first=Corinne|publisher=[[KABC-TV]]|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226035230/https://abc7.com/archive/8625185/|archive-date=December 26, 2018|url-status = dead}}</ref> At the time, [[Mitt Romney]]'s presidential campaign condemned Nugent's remarks; ''Post'' media critic [[Erik Wemple]] noted that there was no response by ''The Washington Times''.<ref name=\":13\" /> In 2014, Nugent (who had by then departed from the ''Times'') described Obama as a \"subhuman [[mongrel]]\", which is a term for mixed-breed dogs.<ref name=\":12\" /> Pruden condemned Nugent's remarks, describing Nugent as an \"aging rock musician with a loose mouth who was semifamous 40 years ago.\"<ref name=\":12\" /> In response to Pruden's condemnation, [[David Weigel]] remarked in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', \"That long ago? Only a year ago, he filed a special column for the ''Washington Times''. Before that, for a few years, he published a weekly column.\".<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nIn 2016, ''The Washington Times'' claimed that $3.6 million in federal funds were spent on a 2013 golf outing for President Obama and [[Tiger Woods]]. ''[[Snopes]]'' rated the article \"mostly false\", because the estimated cost included both official business travel and a brief presidential vacation in [[Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/obama-golf-outing-with-tiger-woods/|title=FALSE: Obama Golf Outing with Tiger Woods Cost Nearly $4 Million|work=Snopes.com|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== Anti-Muslim content ====\nGaffney, known for his \"long history of pushing extreme anti-Muslim views\", wrote weekly columns for ''The Washington Times'' from the late 1990s to 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/12/08/donald-trump-frank-gaffney-islamophobia-poll/|title=Meet Donald Trump's Islamophobia Expert|last=Clifton|first=Eli|website=Foreign Policy|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/03/frank-gaffney-donald-trump-and-the-denationalization-of-american-muslims/519954/|title=Frank Gaffney's Campaign to Denationalize American Muslims|last=Beinart|first=Peter|date=March 19, 2017|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref> According to John Esposito, a Professor of Religion and International Affairs and of Islamic Studies at [[Georgetown University]], Gaffney's \"editorial track record in the ''Washington Times'' is long on accusation and short on supportive evidence.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/the-future-of-islam-9780199975778|title=The Future of Islam|last=Esposito|first=John L.|date=June 27, 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199975778|location=Oxford, New York|pages=19}}</ref> In columns for the ''Times'', Gaffney helped to popularize conspiracy theories that Islamic terrorists were infiltrating the Bush administration, the conservative movement and the Obama administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://press.princeton.edu/titles/10395.html|title=Terrified|last=Bail|first=Christopher|date=|website=Princeton University Press|pages=49\u201351, 99|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/01/frank-gaffney-grover-norquist-muslim-brotherhood_n_1699604.html|title=Frank Gaffney Plotting To Take Down Grover Norquist With Muslim Brotherhood Accusations|last=Terkel|first=Amanda|date=August 1, 2012|work=Huffington Post|access-date=December 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/12/15/cruz-s-cozy-ties-to-dc-s-most-prominent-paranoid-islamophobe|title=Cruz's Cozy Ties To DC's Most Prominent, Paranoid Islamophobe|last=Woodruff|first=Betsy|date=December 15, 2015|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=December 25, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In 2015, the ''Times'' published a column describing refugees fleeing the [[Syrian Civil War]] as an \"Islamic [[Trojan Horse]]\" conducting a \"'jihad' by another name.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/presidential-campaign/262953-the-paranoid-style-in-islamophobic-politics|title=The paranoid style in Islamophobic politics|last=Picard|first=Joe|date=December 14, 2015|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=December 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/monica-crowley-latest-addition-to-trumps-national-security-team-believes-in-fighting-islam-the-way-we-fought-the-nazis-212132606.html|title=Monica Crowley, latest addition to Trump's national security team, believes in fighting Islam 'the way we fought the Nazis'|website=www.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=December 29, 2018}}</ref> In a column on Islam, Nugent wrote, \"If Islam is the religion of peace, then I\u2019m a malnourished, tofu-eating anti-hunter,\" but did clarify \"not all Muslims are religious whacks who deserve a bullet.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/19/ted-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-saided-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-said|title=Nugent: President Obama Is 'Subhuman Mongrel'|last=Jacobs|first=Ben|date=February 19, 2014|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=December 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016 report, the Muslim advocacy group [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations|Council on American-Islamic Relations]] listed ''The Washington Times'' among media outlets it said \"regularly demonstrates or supports Islamophobic themes.\"<ref name=\"deseretnews.com\"/> In 1998 the Egyptian newspaper ''[[Al-Ahram]]'' wrote that its {{'}} editorial policy was \"rabidly anti-[[Arab people|Arab]], anti-Muslim and pro-Israel.\"<ref>[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/1998/403/op1.htm The same old game] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215193404/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/1998/403/op1.htm|date=February 15, 2009}}, ''[[Al-Ahram]]'', November 12\u201318, 1998, \"The Washington Times is a mouthpiece for the ultra conservative right, unquestioning supporters of Israel's [[Likud]] government. The newspaper is owned by Sun Myung Moon, originally a native of North Korea and head of the Unification Church, whose ultra-right leanings make him a ready ally for Netanyahu. Whether or not Netanyahu is personally acquainted with Moon is unclear, though there is no doubt that he has established close friendships with several staff members on ''The Washington Times'', whose editorial policy is rabidly anti-Arab, anti-Muslim and pro-Israel.\"</ref>\n\n=== Other controversies ===\nSome former employees, including Whelan, have insisted that ''The Washington Times'' was always under Moon's control. Whelan, whose contract guaranteed editorial autonomy, left the paper when the owners refused to renew the contract.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/23/us/ex-publisher-says-moon-church-ran-newspaper.html \"Ex-Publisher Says Moon Church Ran Newspaper\"], [[The New York Times]], Susan Rasky, July 23, 1984. Retrieved June 20, 2014.</ref> Three years later, editorial page editor William P. Cheshire and four of his staff resigned, charging that, at the explicit direction of Sang Kook Han, a top official of the Unification movement, then-[[executive editor]] [[Arnaud de Borchgrave]] had stifled editorial criticism of political repression in South Korea under [[President of South Korea|President]] [[Chun Doo-hwan]].<ref>\"Five Resign from ''Washington Times'',\" ''The Washington Post'', April 15, 1987.</ref> In 1982, ''The Washington Times'' refused to publish film critic Scott Sublett's negative review of the movie ''[[Inchon (film)|Inchon]]'', which was also sponsored by the Unification movement.<ref name=\"romano\">{{cite news |last=Romano |first=Lois |title=Review is Killed |work=[[The Washington Post]] |page=C1  |date=September 18, 1982}}</ref>\n\n''The Washington Times'' reporters visited imprisoned [[South Africa]]n [[civil rights]] activist [[Nelson Mandela]] during the 1980s. Mandela wrote of them in his autobiography ''Long Walk to Freedom'', \"They seemed less intent on finding out my views than on proving that I was a Communist and a terrorist. All of their questions were slanted in that direction, and when I reiterated that I was neither a Communist nor a terrorist, they attempted to show that I was not a Christian either by asserting that the Reverend Martin Luther King never resorted to violence.\"<ref name=\":822\"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.littlebrown.com/titles/nelson-mandela/long-walk-to-freedom/9780759521049/|title=Long Walk to Freedom|last=Mandela|first=Nelson|isbn=|location=|pages=315|language=en-US|date=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, ''The Washington Times'' published a misleading story suggesting that Democratic presidential candidate [[Michael Dukakis]] had sought psychiatric help, and included a quote from Dukakis' sister-in-law saying \"it is possible\" he visited a psychiatrist. However, the paper misleadingly clipped the full quote by the sister-in-law, which was, \"It's possible, but I doubt it.\"<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1988/08/13/reporter-quits-over-dukakis-story/a20b4aae-a28c-4dff-85d0-e3bd5d359306/|title=REPORTER QUITS OVER DUKAKIS STORY|last=|first=|date=1988|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> Reporter Peggy Weyrich quit in 1991 after one of her articles about [[Anita Hill]]'s testimony in the [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nominee hearings]] was rewritten to depict Hill as a \"fantasizer.\"<ref name=\":822\"/>\n\nIn a 1997 column, Frank Gaffney falsely alleged a [[seismic]] incident in [[Russia]] was a nuclear detonation at that nation's [[Novaya Zemlya]] test site, which would have meant that Russia had violated the [[Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty]] (CTB).<ref name=\"bas222\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vgwAAAAAMBAJ|title=Spinning to the Right|last1=Isaacs|first1=John|date=November 1997|work=[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> Subsequent scientific analysis of the Novaya Zemlya event showed that it was a routine [[earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.armscontrol.org/print/357|title=False Accusations, Undetected Tests and Implications for the CTB Treaty|last1=Wallace|first1=Terry|work=[[Arms Control Association]]|accessdate=July 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523100845/https://www.armscontrol.org/print/357|archive-date=May 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Reporting on the allegation, the ''[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]'' observed that following its publication \"fax machines around Washington, D.C. and across the country poured out pages detailing Russian duplicity. They came from Frank Gaffney.\" The ''Bulletin'' also noted that during the first four months of 1997, Gaffney had \"issued more than 25 screeds\" against the CTB.<ref name=\"bas222\" />\n\nIn 2002, ''The Washington Times'' published a story accusing the [[National Educational Association]] (NEA), the largest teachers' [[Labor union|union]] in the United States, of teaching students that the policies of the U.S. government were partly responsible for the [[9/11|2001 terrorist attacks]] on the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]].<ref name=\":83\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2002/09/05/nea/|title=The big NEA-Sept. 11 lie|date=September 5, 2002|website=Salon|language=en|access-date=December 24, 2018}}</ref>  Brendan Nyhan (now a [[University of Michigan]] political science professor) wrote that the story was a \"lie\" and a \"myth\".<ref name=\":83\" />  The accusation was denied by the NEA.<ref name=\"The Boston Globe, 2002-09-022\">{{cite news|url=http://cathyyoung.net/bgcolumns/2002/unfair.html|title=An unfair attack on teachers union|last=Young|first=Cathy|date=September 2, 2002|work=Boston Globe|accessdate=April 17, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Letter to ''The Washington Times'' from NEA President|date=August 20, 2002|publisher=[[National Education Association]]|url=http://www.nea.org/nr/nr020820b.html|last=Chase|first=Bob|accessdate=April 17, 2008|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517134505/http://www.nea.org/nr/nr020820b.html|archivedate=May 17, 2008|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 ''The Washington Times'' published a commentary piece by retired U.S. Navy admiral [[James Lyons (admiral)|James A. Lyons]] which promoted conspiracy theories about the [[murder of Seth Rich]]. In the piece, Lyon said that it was \"well known in intelligence circles that Seth Rich and his brother, Aaron Rich, downloaded the [[Democratic National Committee|DNC]] emails and was paid by [[WikiLeaks]] for that information.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> The piece cited no evidence for the assertion.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2018/03/27/brother-of-slain-dnc-staffer-seth-rich-sues-right-wing-activists-newspaper-over-conspiracy-theories/|title=Brother of slain DNC staffer Seth Rich sues right-wing activists, newspaper over conspiracy theories|last=Eltagouri|first=Marwa|date=March 27, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Aaron Rich filed a lawsuit against ''The Washington Times'', saying that it acted with \"reckless disregard for the truth\" and that it did not retract or remove the piece after \"receiving notice of the falsity of the statements about Aaron after the publication\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/05/21/media/seth-rich-brad-bauman-lawsuit/index.html|title=Former Seth Rich family spokesman files lawsuit against individuals, media outlet he says defamed him|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|work=CNNMoney|access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/380452-brother-of-slain-dnc-staffer-sues-washington-times-conservative-activists|title=Brother of slain DNC staffer sues ''Washington Times'', conservative activists|last=Anapol|first=Avery|date=March 27, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Rich and ''The Washington Times'' settled their lawsuit and the paper issued an \"unusually robust\" retraction.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news |last1=Darcy |first1=Oliver |title=''The Washington Times'' settles lawsuit with Seth Rich's brother, issues retraction and apology for its coverage |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/10/01/media/washington-times-aaron-rich/index.html |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |work=CNNMoney}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Retraction: Aaron Rich and the murder of Seth Rich |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/sep/30/retraction-aaron-rich-and-murder-seth-rich/ |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n'''Editors-in-chief'''\n\n*[[James R. Whelan]] (1982\u20131984)\n*[[Smith Hempstone]] (1984\u20131986)\n*[[Arnaud de Borchgrave]] (1986\u20131992)\n*[[Wesley Pruden]] (1992\u20132008)\n*[[John F. Solomon]] (2008\u20132009) (2013\u20132015)\n*[[Sam Dealey]] (2010)\n*[[Ed Kelley]] (2011\u20132012)\n* David S. Jackson (2012\u20132013)\n*[[Christopher Dolan]] (2015\u2013present)\n\n'''Managing editors'''\n\n*[[Josette Sheeran Shiner]] (1992\u20131997)\n*Francis Coombs (?\u20132008)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/times-says-goodbye-to-pruden-coombs/|title=Times Says Goodbye To Pruden, Coombs|website=AdWeek|date=January 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n'''Opinion editors'''\n\n*[[Ann Crutcher]] (1984\u20131985)\n*[[William P. Cheshire]] (1985\u20131987)\n*[[Tony Snow]] (1987\u20131990)\n*[[Tod Lindberg]] (1991\u20131998)\n*[[Tony Blankley]] (2002\u20132007)\n*[[Richard Miniter]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/11/17/AR2009111703325.html|title=Washington Times editor Richard Miniter files discrimination claim|last=Kurtz|first=Howard|date=November 17, 2009|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref> (2009)\n*[[Brett Decker]] (2009\u20132013)\n*[[Wesley Pruden]] (2013)\n*[[David Keene]] (2014\u20132016)\n*[[Charles Hurt]] (2016\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/dec/18/charles-hurt-rejoins-the-washington-times-as-new-o/|title=Charles Hurt rejoins The Washington Times as new opinion editor|work=The Washington Times|date=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''Current contributors'''{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Wesley Pruden]] (editor emeritus and opinion columnist)\n*[[Bill Gertz]] (\"Inside the Ring\" columnist)\n*[[Rowan Scarborough]] (national security writer)\n*[[Donald Lambro]] (chief political correspondent)\n*[[Jennifer Harper]] (\"Inside the Beltway\" columnist)\n*[[Joseph Curl]] (writer and columnist)\n*[[Victor Davis Hanson]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Thom Loverro]] (sports columnist)\n*[[Mark Kellner]] (religion columnist)\n*[[Rita Cook]] (automobile columnist)\n*[[Newt Gingrich]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Jenny Beth Martin]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Richard W. Rahn]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Emmett Tyrrell|R. Emmett Tyrrell, Jr.]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Clifford D. May]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Cal Thomas]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Robert H. Knight]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Peter Morici]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Tammy Bruce]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Charles Hurt]] (opinion editor and columnist)\n*[[Jeffrey Birnbaum]] (columnist)\n*[[Stephen Moore (writer)|Stephen Moore]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Ed Feulner]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Foster Friess]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Allen West (politician)|Allen West]] (opinion columnist){{div col end}}\n\n'''Former contributors'''{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[George Archibald (journalist)|George Archibald]] (congressional, political, United Nations, and education reporter)\n*[[Bruce Bartlett]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]] (editorial writer, film reviewer)\n*[[Amanda Carpenter]] (columnist)\n*[[Ben Carson]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Monica Crowley]] (online opinion editor and columnist)\n*[[Dave Fay]] (editor and journalists, deceased)\n*[[Bruce Fein]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Samuel T. Francis]] (editor and columnist, deceased)\n*[[Frank Gaffney]] (columnist)\n*[[Madison Gesiotto]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Nat Hentoff]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Shirley A. Husar]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Ernest Istook]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Drew Johnson]] (columnist)\n*[[Tom Knott]] (sports columnist)\n*[[Lawrence Kudlow]] (economics columnist)\n*[[Jeffrey T. Kuhner|Jeffrey Kuhner]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Willie Lawson]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Tod Lindberg]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Herbert London]] (opinion columnist) (deceased)\n*[[Michelle Malkin]] (columnist)\n*[[John McCaslin]] (\"Inside the Beltway\" columnist)\n*[[Oliver North]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Ted Nugent]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Rand Paul]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/feb/8/sen-rand-paul-trust-verify-immigration-reform/ |title=Sen. Rand Paul: Trust but verify on immigration reform |work=The Washington Times |date=February 8, 2013 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/nov/5/washington-times-ends-sen-rand-paul-column-amid-pl/ |title=Washington Times ends Sen. Rand Paul column amid plagiarism allegations |work=The Washington Times |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> (opinion columnist)\n*[[Jeremiah O'Leary]] (deceased)\n*[[John Podhoretz]] (columnist)\n*Fred Reed (journalist)\n*[[Rob Redding]] (journalist and talk host)\n*[[Kelly Riddell]] (\"Water Cooler\" columnist)\n*[[James S. Robbins]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Bill Sammon]] (White House correspondent)\n*[[Mercedes Schlapp]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Thomas Sowell]] (columnist)\n*[[Mark Steyn]] (opinion columnist)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/article/20080407/COMMENTARY08/963463285/1012 |title=Closing time at Cafe Clinton? \u2013 - Breaking News, Political News & National Security News \u2013 The Washington Times |date=April 11, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2016 |url-status = unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411170458/http://www.washingtontimes.com/article/20080407/COMMENTARY08/963463285/1012 |archivedate=April 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n*[[Janine Turner]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Harlan K. Ullman|Harlan Ullman]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Diana West]] (opinion columnist)\n{{div col end}}\n'''Others'''\n* [[Daniel Wattenberg]]: Arts and Entertainment editor\n* [[Julia Duin]]: Religion editor\n{{inc-lit}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Journalism}}\n* [[Media in Washington, D.C.]], [[List of newspapers in Washington, D.C.]]\n* ''[[The Washington Star]]'' (1852\u20131981)\n* ''[[The Washington Post]]'' (1877\u2013present)\n* ''[[Washington Times-Herald]]'', a former D.C. daily newspaper founded by [[William Randolph Hearst]] as ''The Evening Times''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026749/ |title=About ''The Washington Times'' (Washington {{bracket|D.C.}}) 1902\u20131939 |work=Chronicling America |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130235120/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026749/ |archive-date=January 30, 2016 |url-status = live|publisher=Library of Congress |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n* [[Washington Times-Herald (Indiana)|''Washington Times-Herald'']], a [[Washington, Indiana]] newspaper\n* [[Unification Church political activities]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Washington Times}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{White House James S. Brady Press Briefing Room Seating Chart}}\n{{Unification Church}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Washington Times, The}}\n[[Category:1982 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Conservative media in the United States]]\n[[Category:National newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Unification Church affiliated organizations]]\n[[Category:Politics of climate change]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the newspaper with a similar name published from 1894 to 1939|Washington Times (1894\u20131939)|the newspaper with a similar name published from 1939 to 1954|Washington Times-Herald}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{short description|American conservative broadsheet newspaper published in Washington, D.C.}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| logo = The Washington Times (2019-10-31).svg\n| image = Washtimesfrontapril5.jpg\n| caption = Front page for August 22, 2016\n| type = [[Daily newspaper]]\n| format = [[Broadsheet]]\n| founder = [[Sun Myung Moon]]\n| publisher = Larry Beasley\n| editor = \n| president = \n| chiefeditor = Christopher Dolan\n| depeditor = \n| assoceditor = \n| maneditor = \n| newseditor = Victor Morton\n| managingeditordesign = Cathy Gainor\n| opeditor = Charles Hurt\n| sportseditor = David Eldridge\n| photoeditor = \n| staff = \n| foundation = {{start date and age|1982|5|17}}\n| political = <!-- Do not fill in without establishing consensus on Talk page. -->\n| language = English\n| ceased publication = \n| relaunched = \n| headquarters = 3600 [[New York Avenue NE]]<br />[[Washington, D.C.]], U.S.\n| circulation = 52,059 daily\n| circulation_date     = 2019\n| circulation_ref      = <ref>{{cite web|url=https://gotoanr.com/documents/database/district-of-columbia.pdf|title=District of Columbia Newspaper Circulation|website=ANR|accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n| sister newspapers = \n| ISSN = 0732-8494\n| oclc = 8472624\n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| free = \n| dirinteractive = \n| logo_size = \n| motto = ''Reliable Reporting. The Right Opinion.'' \n| logo_alt = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| owner = Operations Holdings (via The Washington Times, LLC)\n| generalmanager = David Dadisman<ref>http://twt-media.washtimes.com/media/misc/2016/05/26/RollingThunder_Final.pdf</ref>\n| metroeditor = \n| metrochief = \n| readership = \n| publishing_country = United States\n| publishing_city = Washington, D.C.\n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n'''''The Washington Times''''' is an [[United States|American]] [[daily newspaper]] published in [[Washington, D.C.]], that covers general interest topics with a particular emphasis on [[Politics of the United States|national politics]]. Its [[broadsheet]] daily edition is distributed throughout the [[District of Columbia]] and in parts of [[Maryland]] and [[Virginia]]. A weekly [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] edition aimed at a national audience is also published.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/subscribe/|title=Subscribe}}</ref>\n\n''The Washington Times'' was founded on May 17, 1982, by [[Unification movement]] leader [[Sun Myung Moon]] and owned until 2010 by [[News World Communications]], an international media [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] founded by Moon. It is currently owned by Operations Holdings, which is owned by the Unification movement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/1d470c008efe41e2bd0777173c246f36/washington-times-reports-first-profitable-month|title=The Washington Times reports first profitable month|website=The Big Story|language=en-US|access-date=February 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.operationsholdings.com/about-us/|title=Operations Holdings INC \u2013 About Us|author=|date=|website=www.operationsholdings.com|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThroughout its history, ''The Washington Times'' has been known for its [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] political stance.<ref name=\"Hall\" /><ref name=\"Glaberson\" /><ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":5\" />  It has published many columns which reject the [[scientific consensus]]es on [[climate change]],<ref name=\"Playing Climate-Change Telephone\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/tech/elements/playing-climate-change-telephone|title=Playing Climate-Change Telephone|work=The New Yorker|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://climatefeedback.org/evaluation/tom-harris-deceptive-temperature-record-claims/|title=Analysis of \"Deceptive temperature record claims\"|date=August 28, 2015|work=Climate Feedback|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/hiltzik/la-fi-mh-attack-on-climate-change-scientists-20151204-column.html|title=The attack on climate change scientists continues in Washington|last=Hiltzik|first=Michael|website=Los Angeles Times|date=December 4, 2015}}</ref> on [[ozone depletion]],<ref name=\"handful\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fpMh3nh3JI0C|title=Merchants of Doubt: How a Handful of Scientists Obscured the Truth on Issues from Tobacco Smoke to Global Warming|authors=Naomi Oreskes & Erik M. Conway|publisher=Bloomsbury|pages=130\u2013135|date=2010|isbn=9781608192939}}</ref> on the harmful effects of [[second-hand smoke]],<ref name=\"myths\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.independent.org/news/article.asp?id=2715|title=Anthology of 1995's Environmental Myths|last=Singer|first=Fred|date=1995|work=The Washington Times|access-date=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181229193017/http://www.independent.org/news/article.asp?id=2715|url-status = dead|archive-date=2018-12-29}}</ref><ref name=\"inq climate\">{{Cite book|url=http://cup.columbia.edu/book/the-inquisition-of-climate-science/9780231157193|title=The Inquisition of Climate Science|last=Powell|first=James Lawrence|date=2011|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231527842|location=|pages=57, 198}}</ref>  and which have spread [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|misinformation regarding the 2019-2020 coronavirus outbreak]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Monitoring|first=B. B. C.|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037|title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online|date=2020-01-30|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> \nIt has drawn controversy for publishing [[racism|racist]] content, including commentary and [[conspiracy theories]] about [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Barack Obama]],<ref name=\"Obama\">\n* {{Cite news|author=Betsy Woodruff|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/cruzs-cozy-ties-to-dcs-most-prominent-paranoid-islamophobe|title=Cruz's Cozy Ties To DC's Most Prominent, Paranoid Islamophobe|newspaper=Daily Beast|date=December 15, 2015}}\n* {{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2015/12/08/meet-frank-gaffney-the-anti-muslim-gadfly-who-produced-donald-trumps-anti-muslim-poll/|title=Meet Frank Gaffney, the anti-Muslim gadfly reportedly advising Donald Trump's transition team|last=Bump|first=Philip|date=November 16, 2016|work=The Washington Post}}\n* {{Cite web|author=Eli Clifton|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/12/08/donald-trump-frank-gaffney-islamophobia-poll/|title=Meet Donald Trump's Islamophobia Expert|website=Foreign Policy|date=December 8, 2015}}\n* {{Cite web|author=Robert Schlesinger|url=https://www.usnews.com/opinion/blogs/robert-schlesinger/2009/06/09/the-nutty-obama-is-a-muslim-charge-is-back-now-with-a-hitler-comparison|title=The Nutty 'Obama Is a Muslim' Charge Is Back (Now With a Hitler Comparison!)|work=U.S. News & World Report|date=June 9, 2009}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/brendan-nyhan/pundits-blame-the-victims_b_692327.html|title=Pundits Blame the Victims on Obama Muslim Myth|website=Huffington Post|date=August 24, 2010|author=Brendan Nyhan}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://archives.cjr.org/united_states_project/the_washington_times_takes_a_b.php|title=''The Washington Times'' takes a giant step\u2014backwards|last=Blake|first=Mariah|date=February 11, 2013|work=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=June 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref> supporting  [[neo-Confederate]] [[historical revisionism]],<ref name=\":7\"/> and promoting [[Islamophobia]].<ref name=\"deseretnews.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865656561/Report-says-list-of-6Islamophobic-groups7-reaches-new-high.html|title=Report says list of 'Islamophobic groups' reaches new high|date=June 20, 2016|website=Deseret News|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref> \n\n==History==\n\n===Beginnings===\n''The Washington Times'' was founded in 1982 by [[News World Communications]], an international media [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] associated with the [[Unification movement]] which also owns newspapers in [[South Korea]], [[Japan]], and [[South America]], as well as the [[news agency]] [[United Press International]] (UPI).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/18/us/around-the-nation-sun-myung-moon-paper-appears-in-washington.html |title=Sun Myung Moon Paper Appears in Washington |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 18, 1982}}</ref> [[Bo Hi Pak]], the chief aide of Unification movement founder and leader [[Sun Myung Moon]], was the founding president and the founding chairman of the board.<ref>Pak was founding president of The Washington Times Corporation (1982\u20131992), and founding chairman of the board. [[Bo Hi Pak]], Appendix B: Brief Chronology of the Life of Dr. Bo Hi Pak, in ''Messiah: My Testimony to Rev. Sun Myung Moon, Vol I'' by Bo Hi Pak (2000), Lanham, MD: University Press of America.</ref> Moon asked [[Richard L. Rubenstein]], a rabbi and college professor who had written on the [[Holocaust]], to serve on the board of directors.<ref>\"Rabbi Joins the Board of Moonie Newspaper\", ''[[The Palm Beach Post]]'', May 21, 1978</ref> ''The Washington Times''{{'}} first editor and publisher was [[James R. Whelan]].\n\nAt the time of founding of ''The Washington Times'', Washington had only one major newspaper, ''[[The Washington Post]]''. [[Massimo Introvigne]], in his 2000 book ''The Unification Church'', said that the ''Post'' had been \"the most anti-Unificationist paper in the United States.\"<ref>[http://www.signaturebooks.com/excerpts/unification.htm excerpt] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513174704/http://www.signaturebooks.com/excerpts/unification.htm |date=May 13, 2008 }} The Unification Church Studies in Contemporary Religion, Massimo Introvigne, 2000, Salt Lake City, Utah: Signature Books, {{ISBN|1-56085-145-7}} p. 25</ref> In 2002, at an event held to celebrate the ''Times''{{'}} 20th anniversary, Moon said: \"''The Washington Times'' is responsible to let the American people know about God\" and \"''The Washington Times'' will become the instrument in spreading the truth about God to the world.\"<ref name=\"Washington Post\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/business/2002/05/23/moon-speech-raises-old-ghosts-as-the-times-turns-20/505334e8-8ce6-44eb-a767-ee7895107cae/|title=Moon Speech Raises Old Ghosts as the Times Turns 20|last=Ahrens|first=Frank|date=May 23, 2002|work=The Washington Post|via=|accessdate=August 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n''The Washington Times'' was founded the year after the ''[[Washington Star]]'', the previous \"second paper\" of D.C., went out of business. A large percentage of the staff came from the ''Star''. When it launched, it was unusual among American [[broadsheet]]s in publishing a full color front page, along with full color front pages in all its sections and color elements throughout. It also used ink that it advertised as being less likely to come off on the reader's hands than the type used by the ''Post''.<ref name=\"'70s 146\">{{cite book |title=How We Got Here: The '70s |last=Frum |first=David |authorlink=David Frum |year=2000 |publisher=Basic Books |location=New York City |isbn=978-0-465-04195-4 |page=[https://archive.org/details/howwegothere70sd00frum/page/146 146] |url=https://archive.org/details/howwegothere70sd00frum/page/146 |url-access=registration }}</ref> At its start, it had 125 reporters, 25 percent of whom were members of the [[Unification Church of the United States]].<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/national/longterm/cult/unification/wtimes.htm The Nation's Capital Gets A New Daily Newspaper],''[[The Washington Post]]'', May 17, 1982</ref>\n\nAfter a brief editorship under [[Smith Hempstone]], de Borchgrave (formerly of UPI and ''[[Newsweek]]'') was executive editor from 1985 to 1991.<ref name=Gamarekian>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/05/18/us/washington-times-editor-resigns-but-will-stay-on-to-write-articles.html|title=''Washington Times'' Editor Resigns, But Will Stay On to Write Articles|year=1991|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|author=Barbara Gamarekian}}</ref> Borchgrave was credited for encouraging energetic reporting by staff, but was known to make unorthodox journalistic decisions. During his tenure, ''The Washington Times'' mounted a fundraising drive for [[Contras|Contra]] rebels in [[Nicaragua]] and offered rewards for information leading to the arrest of [[Nazi war criminals]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/17/business/media/arnaud-de-borchgrave-a-journalist-whose-life-was-a-tale-itself-dies-at-88.html|title=Arnaud de Borchgrave, Journalist Whose Life Was a Tale Itself, Dies at 88|last=Roberts|first=Sam|date=February 16, 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=March 11, 2016}}</ref><ref>Emily Langer, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/arnaud-de-borchgrave-swashbuckling-newsweek-foreign-correspondent-dies/2015/02/15/52609204-b552-11e4-a200-c008a01a6692_story.html Arnaud de Borchgrave, swashbuckling Newsweek foreign correspondent, dies], ''The Washington Post'' (February 15, 2015).</ref>\n\n[[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Ronald Reagan]] is said to have read ''The Washington Times'' every day during his presidency.<ref name=\"Behind the Times\">[http://www.fair.org/index.php?page=1569 Behind the Times] [[Fairness and Accuracy in Reporting]] August/September 1987</ref> In 1997 he said, \"The American people know the truth. You, my friends at ''The Washington Times'', have told it to them. It wasn't always the popular thing to do. But you were a loud and powerful voice. Like me, you arrived in Washington at the beginning of the most momentous decade of the century. Together, we rolled up our sleeves and got to work. And\u2014oh, yes\u2014we won the [[Cold War]].\"<ref name=\"Dear Leader's Paper Moon\">[http://prospect.org/article/dear-leaders-paper-moon Dear Leader's Paper Moon] [[The American Prospect]] September 19, 2005</ref>\n\n===Wesley Pruden editorship===\n[[Wesley Pruden|Wesley \"Wes\" Pruden]], previously a correspondent and then a [[managing editor]], was named executive editor in 1991.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite news|url=http://archives.cjr.org/year/95/2/times.asp|title=Washington's Other Paper|last=|first=|date=1995|work=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=|archive-url=https://archive.today/20040223081524/http://archives.cjr.org/year/95/2/times.asp|archive-date=February 23, 2004|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref> During his editorship, the paper took a strongly [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] and [[Nativism (politics)|nativist]] stance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cjr.org/united_states_project/the_washington_times_takes_a_b.php|title=The Washington Times takes a giant step\u2014backwards|website=Columbia Journalism Review|access-date=March 11, 2016}}</ref>[[File:2008 07 The Washington Times newsroom 02.jpg|thumb|247x247px|''The Washington Times'' newsroom]]\n\nIn 1992, [[North Korea]]n leader [[Kim Il Sung]] gave his first and only interview with the Western news media to ''The Washington Times'' reporter [[Josette Sheeran]], who later became Executive Director of the [[United Nations World Food Programme]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/11/world/americas/11sheeran.html?pagewanted=all A Desire to Feed the World and Inspire Self-Sufficiency], ''New York Times'', August 11, 2007</ref> At the time, ''The Washington Times'' had one-eighth the circulation of the ''Post'' (100,000 compared to 800,000) and two-thirds of its subscribers subscribed to both papers.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1992/01/27/business/the-media-business-washington-times-moves-to-reinvent-itself.html Washington Times Moves to Reinvent Itself], Alex S. Jones, ''[[The New York Times]]'', January 27, 1992.</ref> In 1994 it introduced a weekly \"national edition\" which was published in a [[tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]] format and distributed nationwide.<ref name=\"nyt1994\">[https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/27/business/the-media-business-conservative-daily-tries-to-expand-national-niche.html?pagewanted=all Conservative Daily Tries to Expand National Niche], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 27, 1994</ref>\n\nU.S. President [[George H. W. Bush]] encouraged the political influence of ''The Washington Times'' and other Unification movement activism in support of American [[foreign policy]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Goodman |first=Walter |date=January 21, 1992 |title=Review/Television; Sun Myung Moon Changes Robes |periodical=New York Times |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CEEDB1F3FF932A15752C0A964958260&sec=&spon=}}</ref> In 1997, the ''[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]],'' which is critical of U.S. and [[Israel]]i policies, praised ''The Washington Times'' and its sister publication, ''[[News World Communications|The Middle East Times]]'', for what it called their objective and informative coverage of [[Islam]] and the [[Middle East]], while criticizing their generally pro-Israel editorial policy. The ''Report'' suggested that these newspapers, being owned by religious institutions, were less influenced by pro-Israel pressure groups in the U.S.<ref>[http://www.wrmea.com/backissues/1297/9712060.html As U.S. Media Ownership Shrinks, Who Covers Islam?] {{webarchive |url=http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20050421165328/http://www.wrmea.com/backissues/1297/9712060.html |date=April 21, 2005 }}, ''[[Washington Report on Middle East Affairs]]'', December 1997</ref>\n\nIn 2004, ''Post'' columnist [[David Ignatius]] reported that [[Chung Hwan Kwak]], a top leader of the Unification movement, wanted ''The Washington Times'' to \"support international organizations such as the [[United Nations]] and to campaign for world peace and interfaith understanding.\" This, Ignatius wrote, created difficulties for Pruden and some of the ''Times''{{'}} columnists. Ignatius also mentioned the Unification movement's reconciliatory attitude towards North Korea, which at the time included joint business ventures, and Kwak's advocacy for greater understanding between the U.S. and the [[Islamic world]] as issues of contention. Ignatius predicted that conservatives in Congress and the [[George W. Bush]] administration would support Pruden's position over Kwak's.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A50909-2004Jun17.html Tension of the Times] ''[[The Washington Post]]'' June 18, 2004, \"Insiders say the church's new line is that with the end of the Cold War, it's important to support international organizations such as the United Nations and to campaign for world peace and interfaith understanding. That stance would be awkward for ''The Washington Times''{{'}}s hard-line editor in chief, Wesley Pruden, and its stable of neoconservative columnists.\"</ref>\n\n===John Solomon editorship===\n[[File:2008 09 The Washington Times - Printing and Distribution Center.jpg|thumb|The printing and distribution center of ''The Washington Times'']]\nIn January 2008, Pruden retired and [[John F. Solomon]] began as executive editor. Solomon had previously worked for the [[Associated Press]], and had most recently been head of [[investigative reporting]] and mixed media development at the ''Post''.<ref>[http://www.connpost.com/ci_8089629?source=rss State Native to lead DC newspaper] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211111011/http://www.connpost.com/ci_8089629?source=rss |date=February 11, 2009 }} ''[[Connecticut Post]]'' January 26, 2008</ref><ref>[http://biz.yahoo.com/nytimes/080211/1194745974399.html?.v=4 Ex-''Washington Post'' Reporter to Lead a Rival] ''[[The New York Times]]'' February 11, 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Erik Wemple|url=http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/display.php?id=34649|title=Playing Center: John Solomon is pushing evenhandedness at ''The Washington Times''|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080301235126/http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/display.php?id=34649 |archive-date=March 1, 2008 |work=[[Washington City Paper]]|date=February 29, 2008}}</ref> Within a month, ''The Washington Times'' changed some of its [[style guide]] to conform more to what was becoming mainstream media usage. It announced that it would no longer use words like \"[[illegal immigration|illegal aliens]]\" and \"[[homosexuality|homosexual]]\", and in most cases opt for \"more neutral terminology\" like \"illegal immigrants\" and \"gay,\" respectively. It also decided to stop using \"Hillary\" when referring to [[United States Senator|Senator]] [[Hillary Clinton]], and the word \"marriage\" in the expression \"[[gay marriage]]\" would no longer appear in quotes in the newspaper. These changes in policy drew criticism from some conservatives.<ref name=salonfeb>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/politics/war_room/2008/02/26/washington_times/index.html |title=''Washington Times'' updates style guide, conservatives up in arms |work=Salon |date=February 27, 2008 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'' magazine attributed the ''Times''{{'}} apparent political moderation to differences of opinion over the UN and North Korea, and said: \"The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] right may be losing its most devoted media ally.\"<ref>[http://www.prospect-magazine.co.uk/article_details.php?id=7720 News and Curiosities], ''[[Prospect (magazine)|Prospect]]'', September 2006</ref>[[File:Washington Times dispenser.jpg|thumb|200px|''Times'' dispenser]]\n\nIn July 2010, the Unification Church issued a letter protesting the direction ''The Washington Times'' was taking and urging closer ties with it.<ref>[http://www.poynter.org/column.asp?id=45&aid=187388 Unification Church CEO, others respond to unsigned blog post about ''Washington Times''] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724054956/http://www.poynter.org/column.asp?id=45&aid=187388 |date=July 24, 2010 }}, Poynter Online (website of the [[Poynter Institute]]), July 22, 2010</ref> In August 2010, a deal was made to sell it to a group more closely related to the movement. [[Editor-in-chief]] [[Sam Dealey]] said that this was a welcome development among the ''Times''{{'}} staff.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/25/business/media/25times.html?_r=1&dbk Deal in Works for ''The Washington Times''], ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 25, 2010</ref> In November 2010, Moon and a group of former editors purchased ''The Washington Times'' from News World Communications for $1. This ended a conflict within the Moon family that had been threatening to shut down the paper completely.<ref>{{cite news |title=Moon group buys back ''Washington Times'' |work=The Washington Post |date=November 3, 2010 |page=C1 |first=Ian |last=Shapira}}</ref>  In June 2011, Ed Kelley, formerly of ''[[The Oklahoman]]'', was hired as editor overseeing both news and opinion content.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/washington-times-names-ed-kelley-as-editor-will-oversee-news-coverage-and-opinion-content/2011/06/10/AGP2gqOH_story.html ''Washington Times'' names Ed Kelley as editor; will oversee news coverage and opinion content], ''[[The Washington Post]]'', June 10, 2011</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Douglas D. M. Joo stepped down as senior executive, president, and chairman.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Longtime Times executive Joo resigns, takes job in Korea|url = http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/oct/14/longtime-times-executive-joo-resigns/|work= The Washington Times|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref> ''Times'' president Tom McDevitt took his place as chairman, and Larry Beasley was hired as the company's new president and [[chief executive officer]].<ref>{{Cite news|title = New Times CEO moves quickly to name leadership team, set path to profitability|url = http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/oct/16/new-times-ceo-moves-quickly-name-leadership-team-s/?page=1|work= The Washington Times|access-date = February 7, 2016}}</ref>  In 2013, it worked with Herring Networks to create a new conservative cable news channel, [[One America News]], which began broadcasting in mid\u20112013.<ref>{{cite news |title=''The Washington Times'' extending reach with cable network |first=Jennifer |last=Harper |url=http://m.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/mar/13/the-washington-times-extending-reach-cable-network/ |newspaper=The Washington Times |date=March 13, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}<br />{{cite news |title=One America News Network, New Conservative Cable Channel, Sets Launch |first=David |last=Freedlander |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2013/03/14/one-america-news-network-new-conservative-cable-channel-sets-launch.html |newspaper=Daily Beast |date=March 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}<br />{{cite news |title=Herring Plans to Launch New Conservative News Network |first=Keach |last=Hagey |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324392804578358743706989224 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=March 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013  ''The Washington Times'' hired [[David Keene]], the former president of the [[National Rifle Association]] and [[American Conservative Union]] chairman, to serve as its opinion editor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/07/david-keene-exnra-president-named-washington-times-168277.html|title=David Keene, ex-NRA president, named Washington Times opinion editor|last=Byers|first=Dylan|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=December 26, 2018}}</ref> Around the same time, Solomon returned as editor and also served as vice president of content and business development.<ref>{{Cite news|title = Solomon returns to lead content, business strategies at ''The Washington Times''|url = http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/jul/8/solomon-returns-lead-content-business-strategies-w/?page=1|access-date = February 7, 2016|work= The Washington Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jimromenesko.com/2013/07/08/john-solomon-returns-to-the-washington-times/|title=John Solomon returns to ''The Washington Times''|website=JIMROMENESKO.COM|access-date=April 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160423010844/http://jimromenesko.com/2013/07/08/john-solomon-returns-to-the-washington-times/|archive-date=April 23, 2016|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref>  Solomon's tenure was marked by a focus on profitability. He left for [[Circa News]] in December 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/12/07/john-solomon-leaves-washington-times-joins-circa-re-launch/|title=John Solomon leaves Washington Times, joins Circa re-launch|last=Wemple|first=Erik|date=December 7, 2015|website=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Finances===\nIn 1991, Moon said he had spent between $900 million and $1 billion on ''The Washington Times''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unification.net/1991/911223.html|title=Reverend Sun Myung Moon Speaks on Our Mission During the Time of World Transition|author=Damian Anderson|date=December 23, 1991|publisher=Unification.net|accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref> By 2002, Moon had spent between $1.7 billion and $2 billion according to different estimates.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn?pagename=article&contentId=A60061-2002May22 |work=The Washington Post |title=Moon Speech Raises Old Ghosts as the Times Turns 20 |first=Frank |last=Ahrens |date=May 23, 2002 |accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"wash-chinni.asp2\" />  In November 2009, ''The New York Times'' reported that ''The Washington Times'' would no longer be receiving funds from the Unification movement and might have to cease publication or become an [[online publication]] only.<ref name=\"nyt1212009\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/01/business/media/01moon.html With Tumult at the Top, ''Washington Times'' Faces Uncertainty], ''[[The New York Times]]'', November 30, 2009.</ref> Later that year, it fired 40 percent of its 370 employees and stopped its subscription service, instead distributing the paper free in some areas of Washington including branches of the government. A subscription website owned by the paper, theconservatives.com, continued, as did the ''Times''{{'}} three-hour [[radio program]], ''America's Morning News''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/03/business/media/03paper.html Large Staff Cuts Announced at ''The Washington Times''], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 2, 2009</ref> The paper announced that it would cease publication of its Sunday edition, along with other changes, partly in order to end its reliance on subsidies from the Unification movement.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20190305144454/http://www.editorandpublisher.com/eandp/news/article_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1004054777 ''Washington Times'' Dropping Sunday Edition As Part of 'Refocused' Approach], ''[[Editor & Publisher]]'', December 21, 2009</ref> On December 31, 2009, ''The Washington Times'' announced that it would no longer be a full-service newspaper, eliminating its metropolitan-news and sports sections.<ref>[http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/local/ap/washington-times-cuts-sports-section-others-80415182.html ''Washington Times'' cuts sports section, others]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''[[Washington Examiner]]'', December 31, 2009</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2010/jan/01/daly-the-end-of-times/?page=2 Eulogy for sports], ''The Washington Times'', January 3, 2010</ref>  In March 2011, it announced that some former staffers would be rehired and that the paper would bring back its sports, metro, and life sections.<ref>[http://www.politico.com/blogs/onmedia/0311/Washington_Times_relaunching_Monday.html ''Washington Times'' relaunching Monday], [[Politico (newspaper)|Politico]], March 16, 2011</ref>  It had its first profitable month in September 2015, ending the streak of losses in the paper's first 33 years.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jennifer Harper|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/oct/14/washington-times-reaches-profitability-after-33-ye/?page=1|title=''Washington Times'' reaches profitability after 33 years, $1 billion in losses|work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n\n==Political stance, content and controversies==\n''The Washington Times'' holds a [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] political stance.<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite news |last=Hall |first=Mimi |title=Bush, aides boost access of conservative media |work=USA Today |date=March 22, 2001|url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/politics/2001-03-22-media.htm}}</ref><ref name=\"Glaberson\">{{cite news |last=Glaberson |first=William |title=Conservative Daily Tries to Expand National Niche |work=The New York Times |date=June 27, 1994|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/06/27/business/the-media-business-conservative-daily-tries-to-expand-national-niche.html |accessdate=July 25, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/03/27/media/seth-rich-brother-sues-washington-times/index.html|title=Seth Rich's brother sues right-wing activists, ''Washington Times'' over conspiracy theories|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|work=CNNMoney|access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.palgrave.com/gp/book/9783319711102|title=Islam, Securitization, and US Foreign Policy {{!}} Erdoan A. Shipoli {{!}} Palgrave Macmillan|last=|first=|year=|isbn=|location=|page=247|language=en}}</ref> ''[[The Columbia Journalism Review]]'' wrote in 1995, that the paper \"is like no major city daily in America in the way that it wears its political heart on its sleeve. No major paper in America would dare be so partisan.\"<ref name=\":18\" /> The ''Post'' reported in 2002, that it \"was established by Moon to [[Anti-communism|combat communism]] and be a conservative alternative to what he perceived as the [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] leanings of ''The Washington Post''. Since then, the paper has fought to prove its editorial independence, trying to demonstrate that it is neither a \"Moonie paper\" nor a booster of the political right but rather a fair and balanced reporter of the news.\"<ref name=\"Washington Post\" /> ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' reported in 2007 that it had become \"essential reading for political news junkies\" soon after its founding, and described the paper as a \"conservative newspaper with close ties to every Republican administration since Reagan.\"<ref>[https://www.motherjones.com/washington_dispatch/2007/04/bush_moon.html Bush Sr. To Celebrate Rev. Sun Myung Moon\u2014Again] ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]'' April 29, 2007</ref>\n\nIn a ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'' essay in 2008, American historian<ref>{{Cite web|title=Bill Moyers Journal. Bill Moyers interviews Thomas Frank |publisher=PBS|url=https://www.pbs.org/moyers/journal/08012008/profile3.html|access-date=February 6, 2016}}</ref> [[Thomas Frank]] linked ''The Washington Times'' to the modern American conservative movement, saying, \"There is even a daily newspaper\u2014''The Washington Times''\u2014published strictly for the movement's benefit, a [[propaganda]] sheet whose distortions are so obvious and so alien that it puts one in mind of those official party organs one encounters when traveling in [[authoritarianism|authoritarian]] countries.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.harpers.org/archive/2008/08/0082132|title=x|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> ''The New York Times'' noted in 2009 that it had been \"a crucial training ground for many rising conservative journalists and a must-read for those in the movement. A veritable who's who of conservatives\u2014[[Tony Blankley]], [[Frank J. Gaffney Jr.]], [[Larry Kudlow]], [[John Podhoretz]] and [[Tony Snow]]\u2014has churned out copy for its pages.\"<ref name=\"nyt1212009\" /> ''The Columbia Journalism Review'' noted that reporters for the ''Times'' had used it as a springboard to other mainstream news outlets.<ref name=\"wash-chinni.asp2\">[http://www.cjr.org/issues/2002/5/wash-chinni.asp Washington 2002: The Other Paper] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419012416/http://www.cjr.org/issues/2002/5/wash-chinni.asp|date=April 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, ''Post'' veteran [[Ben Bradlee]] said, \"I see them get some local stories that I think the ''Post'' doesn't have and should have had.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cjr.org/issues/2002/5/wash-stability.asp|title=Washington 2002: Donald Graham's ''Washington Post''|author=|date=November 24, 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031124234138/http://www.cjr.org/issues/2002/5/wash-stability.asp|archivedate=November 24, 2003|url-status = dead|accessdate=March 19, 2018|df=}}</ref> In January 2011, conservative commentator [[Paul Weyrich]] said, \"''The Washington Post'' became very arrogant and they just decided that they would determine what was news and what wasn't news and they wouldn't cover a lot of things that went on. And ''The Washington Times'' has forced the ''Post'' to cover a lot of things that they wouldn't cover if the ''Times'' wasn't in existence.\"<ref>[http://www.mediachannel.org/originals/moontranscript.shtml MediaChannel.org \u2013 Frontline: Reverend Moon] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110107074820/http://www.mediachannel.org/originals/moontranscript.shtml|date=January 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOpinion editor [[Charles Hurt]] was one of [[Donald Trump]]'s earliest supporters in Washington.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/07/the-trump-show-214075|title=The Trump Dynasty Takes Over the GOP|last=|first=|date=|website=politico.com|access-date= May 3, 2017}}</ref> In 2018 he included Trump with Ronald Reagan, Martin Luther King, [[Margaret Thatcher]], and [[Pope]] [[John Paul II]] as \"great champions of freedom.\"<ref>The Corrosion of Conservatism: Why I Left the Right, [[Max Boot]], Liveright Publishing, October 9, 2018, page 124</ref>\n\n=== Science coverage ===\n==== Climate change denial ====\n''The Washington Times'' is known for promoting [[climate change denial]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=McCright|first=Aaron M.|last2=Dunlap|first2=Riley E.|date=August 18, 2011|title=Organized Climate Change Denial|url=http://www.oxfordhandbooks.com/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199566600.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199566600-e-10|journal=The Oxford Handbook of Climate Change and Society|language=en|volume=|pages=152|doi=10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199566600.003.0010|via=}}</ref><ref name=\":20\" /><ref name=\":21\" /><ref name=\"Playing Climate-Change Telephone\" /><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> [[Michael E. Mann]], director of the Earth System Science Center at [[Pennsylvania State University]], characterizes the ''Times'' as a prominent outlet that propagates \"climate change disinformation.\"<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite book|url=http://cup.columbia.edu/book/the-hockey-stick-and-the-climate-wars/9780231152549|title=The Hockey Stick and the Climate Wars: Dispatches from the Front Lines|last=Mann|first=Michael E.|date=March 2012|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231526388|location=|pages=64}}</ref> [[Naomi Oreskes]], Professor of the History of Science at [[Harvard University]], and [[Erik M. Conway]], historian of science at [[NASA]]'s Jet Propulsion Laboratory at the [[California Institute of Technology]], wrote in their 2010 book ''[[Merchants of Doubt]]'' that the ''Times'' has given the public a false sense that the science of anthropogenic climate change was in dispute by giving disproportionate coverage of fringe viewpoints and by preventing scientists from rebutting coverage in the ''Times''.<ref name=\":21\">{{Cite journal|last=Kitcher|first=Philip|date=June 4, 2010|title=The Climate Change Debates|journal=Science|language=en|volume=328|issue=5983|pages=1230\u20131234|doi=10.1126/science.1189312|issn=1095-9203|bibcode=2010Sci...328.1230K|doi-access=free}}</ref> For example, the paper reprinted a column by [[Steve Milloy]] criticizing research of [[climate change in the Arctic]], without disclosing Milloy's financial ties to the [[fossil fuel]] industry.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Naomi Oreskes & Erik M. Conway|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fpMh3nh3JI0C|title=Merchants of Doubt: How a Handful of Scientists Obscured the Truth on Issues from Tobacco Smoke to Global Warming|date=2010|publisher=Bloomsbury|page=247|isbn=9781608192939}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Climatic Research Unit email controversy]] (also known as \"Climategate\") in 2009 in the lead-up to the [[2009 United Nations Climate Change Conference|UN Climate Change Conference in Copenhagen]], the ''Times'' wrote in an editorial \"these revelations of fudged science should have a cooling effect on global-warming hysteria and the panicked policies that are being pushed forward to address the unproven theory.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shorensteincenter.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/d72_mayer.pdf|title=Stories of Climate Change: Competing Narratives, the Media, and U.S. Public Opinion 2001-2010|last=Mayer|first=Frederick|date=2012|website=|access-date=}}</ref> Eight committees investigated the controversy, and found no evidence of fraud or scientific misconduct. In 2010, the ''Times'' published an article claiming that February 2010 snow storms \"Undermin[e] The Case For Global Warming One Flake At A Time\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/02/09/washington-times-february_n_455199.html|title=Washington Times: February Snow Storms \"Undermin[e] The Case For Global Warming One Flake At A Time\"|last=|first=|date=2010|newspaper=The Huffington Post|access-date=}}</ref> A 2014 ''Times'' editorial mocked the \"global warming scam\" and asserted, \"The planetary thermometer hasn\u2019t budged in 15 years. Wildfires, tornadoes, hurricanes and other \u2018extreme\u2019 weather events are at normal or below-normal levels. Pacific islands aren't submerged. There's so much ice the polar bears are celebrating.\"<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite journal|last=Corneliussen|first=Steven Corneliussen Steven T.|date=July 1, 2014|title=News dispatches from the climate wars|journal=Physics Today|language=EN|doi=10.1063/PT.5.8054}}</ref> The ''Times'' cited a blog post in support of these claims; ''[[PolitiFact]]'' fact-checked the claims in the blog post and concluded it was \"pants-on-fire\" false.<ref name=\":19\" /> The ''Times'' later said that a NASA scientist claimed that global warming was on a \"hiatus\" and that NASA had found evidence of [[global cooling]]; Rebecca Leber of ''[[The New Republic]]'' said that the NASA scientist in question said the opposite of what the ''Times'' claimed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/119033/conservatives-misrepresent-climate-scientist|title=The Right-Wing Press' New Climate Change Lie|work=The New Republic|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2015, it published a column by [[Member of Congress|Congressman]] [[Lamar Smith]] in which he argued that the work of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] was \"not good science, [but] science fiction.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 1993, ''The Washington Times'' published articles purporting to debunk climate change.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/09/14/science/scientists-confront-renewed-backlash-on-global-warming.html|title=Scientists Confront Renewed Backlash on Global Warming|last=Stevens|first=William K.|date=September 14, 1993|work=The New York Times|access-date=December 28, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It headlined its story about the [[1997 Kyoto Protocol]] on climate change, \"Under the deal, the use of coal, oil and other fossil fuel in the United States would be cut by more than one-third by 2002, resulting in lower standards of living for consumers and a long-term reduction in economic growth.\"<ref name=\":822\">{{Cite web|url=https://global.oup.com/ushe/product/reporting-from-washington-9780195308921|title=Reporting from Washington|last=Ritchie|first=Donald|date=|website=|publisher=Oxford University Press|pages=262\u2013263|language=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==== Ozone depletion denial====\nIn the 1990s, ''The Washington Times'' published columns which cast doubt on the scientific consensus on the causes of [[ozone depletion]] (which had led to an \"ozone hole\"). It published columns disputing the science as late as 2000.<ref name=\"handful\"/> In 1991, NASA scientists warned of the potential of a major Arctic ozone hole developing in the spring of 1992 due to elevated levels of [[chlorine monoxide]] in the Arctic [[stratosphere]]. However, as the Arctic winter was unusually warm, the chemical reactions needed for ozone depletion did not occur. Even though the science was not incorrect, the ''Times''', along with other conservative media, subsequently created a \"[[The boy who cried wolf|crying wolf]]\" narrative where scientists were portrayed as political activists who were following an environmental agenda rather than the science. In 1992, it published an editorial saying, \"This is not the disinterested, objective, just-the-facts tone one ordinarily expects from scientists... This is the cry of the apocalyptic, laying the groundwork for a decidedly non-scientific end: public policy... it would be nice if the next time NASA cries 'wolf,' fewer journalists, politicians and citizens heed the warning like sheep.\"<ref>{{Cite journal|date=February 1, 2013|title=Climate change prediction: Erring on the side of least drama?|url= |journal=Global Environmental Change|language=en|volume=23|issue=1|pages=327\u2013337|doi=10.1016/j.gloenvcha.2012.10.008|issn=0959-3780|last1=Brysse|first1=Keynyn|last2=Oreskes|first2=Naomi|last3=o'Reilly|first3=Jessica|last4=Oppenheimer|first4=Michael}}</ref>\n\n==== Second-hand smoke denial====\nIn 1995, ''The Washington Times'' published a column by [[Fred Singer]], who is known for promoting views contrary to mainstream science on a number of issues, where Singer referred to the science on the adverse health impact of [[second-hand smoke]] as the \"second-hand smoke scare\", and accused the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] of distorting data when it classified second-hand smoke as harmful.<ref name=\"myths\"/><ref name=\"inq climate\"/> In 1995 it published an editorial titled \"How not to spend science dollars\" condemning a grant to the National Cancer Institute to study how political contributions from tobacco companies shape policy-making and the voting behavior of politicians.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Landman|first=Anne|last2=Glantz|first2=Stanton A.|date=2009|title=Tobacco Industry Efforts to Undermine Policy-Relevant Research|journal=American Journal of Public Health|volume=99|issue=1|pages=45\u201358|doi=10.2105/AJPH.2007.130740|issn=0090-0036|pmc=2600597|pmid=19008508}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.industrydocumentslibrary.ucsf.edu/tobacco/docs/#id=xkyk0101|title=How not to spend science dollars|last=|first=|date=1995|work=The Washington Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n====Misreporting on the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic====\nIn January 2020, ''The Washington Times'' published two widely shared articles about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] that suggested that the virus was created by China as a [[biological weapon]]. The article quotes a former Israeli intelligence officer as a source, but offered no evidence to support its claims. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Monitoring|first=B. B. C.|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-trending-51271037|title=China coronavirus: Misinformation spreads online|date=2020-01-30|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== White nationalism, neo-Confederatism, racism, and Islamophobia ===\nUnder Pruden's editorship (1992\u20132008), ''The Washington Times'' regularly printed excerpts from racist hard-right publications including ''[[VDARE]]'' and ''[[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]]'', and [[Bill White (neo-Nazi)|Bill White]], leader of the American [[National Socialism|National Socialist]] Workers' Party, in its Culture Briefs section.<ref name=\":4\" /> [[Robert Stacy McCain]], a member of the [[neo-Confederate]] white-supremacist group [[League of the South]], was hired and promoted to edit the Culture Briefs section, which became, according to [[Max Blumenthal]], \"a bulletin board for the racialist far right.\" Blumenthal also wrote that ''The Washington Times'' was \"characterized by extreme racial animus and connections to nativist and neo-Confederate organizations... from its earliest days the ''Times'' has been a hothouse for hard-line racialists and neo-Confederates.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thenation.com/article/hell-times/|title=Hell of a Times|work=The Nation|last=Blumenthal|first=Max|date=September 20, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/palins-noxious-ghostwriter|title=Palin's Noxious Ghostwriter|last=Blumenthal|first=Max|date=November 16, 2009|work=The Daily Beast}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2013 article, the ''Columbia Journalism Review'' reported that under Pruden's editorship ''The Washington Times'' was \"a forum for the racialist hard right, including [[white nationalism|white nationalists]], neo-Confederates, and anti-immigrant scare mongers.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> Between 1998 and 2004, the ''Times'' covered every biennial American Renaissance conference, hosted by the [[white supremacy|white supremacist]] [[New Century Foundation]]. According to the ''Columbia Journalism Review'', \"the paper's coverage of these events\u2014which are hotbeds for [[Holocaust denial|holocaust deniers]], [[neo-Nazi]]s, and [[eugenics|eugenicists]]\u2014was stunningly one sided\", and favorably depicted the conference and attendees.<ref name=\":4\" /> In 2009, journalist [[David Neiwert]] wrote that it championed \"various white-nationalist causes emanating from the neo-Confederate movement (with which, until a recent housecleaning, two senior editors had long associations.)\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RdlqCwAAQBAJ|title=Eliminationists: How Hate Talk Radicalized the American Right|last=Neiwert|first=David|date=2009|publisher=Paradigm Publishers|edition=2016 Routledge|page=80|isbn=9781317260615}}</ref>\n\nA page in ''The Washington Times''{{'}} Sunday edition was devoted to the [[American Civil War]]. The [[Confederate States of America|Confederacy]] was described with admiration several times in the article.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|author=Moe Tkacik|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/news/article/13039788/just-like-old-times-at-the-washington-times|title=Just Like Old Times at ''The Washington Times''?|work=Washington City Paper|date=November 5, 2010}}</ref> In 1993, Pruden gave an interview to the neo-Confederate magazine ''[[Southern Partisan]]'' where he said, \"Every year I make sure that we have a story in the paper about any [[Robert E. Lee Day|observance of Robert E. Lee's birthday]].\"<ref name=\":7\" /> Pruden said, \"And the fact that it falls around [[Martin Luther King]]\u2019s birthday,\" to which a ''Southern Partisan'' interviewer interjected, \"Makes it all the better,\" with Pruden finishing, \"I make sure we have a story. Oh, yes.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n''The Washington Times'' employed [[Samuel T. Francis]], a white nationalist, as a columnist and editor, beginning in 1991 after he was chosen by [[Pat Buchanan]] to take over his column.<ref name=\":9\">Heidi Berich and Kevin Hicks, \"[https://books.google.com/books?id=M7p6TDR1zwcC White Nationalism in America]\" in ''Hate Crimes'' (ed. Barbara Perr: Praeger, 2009), pp. 112\u201313.</ref>''<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2016/aug/16/secret-history-trumpism-donald-trump|title=The dark history of Donald Trump's rightwing revolt|last=Shenk|first=Timothy|date=August 16, 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Fascism: Post-war fascisms|last=Griffin|first=Roger|last2=Feldman|first2=Matthew|publisher=Routledge|year=2004|isbn=|location=|pages=155}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/9781134201570/chapters/10.4324/9780203402191-10|chapter=The American Radical Right: The 1990s and Beyond|last=Potok|first=Mark|title=Western Democracies and the New Extreme Right Challenge|editor1=Roger Eatwell |editor2=Cas Mudde|page=59|publisher=Routledge|date=2003|doi=10.4324/9780203402191|isbn=9780203402191}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dnrkXM1C-eIC|title=Habits of Whiteness: A Pragmatist Reconstruction|last=MacMullan|first=Terrance|date=2009|publisher=Indiana University Press|page=147|isbn=978-0253002884}}</ref> In 1995, Francis resigned or was forced out after [[Dinesh D'Souza]] reported on racist comments that Francis made at a conference hosted by ''American Renaissance'' the previous year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.uncpress.org/book/9780807849606/the-rebuke-of-history|title=The Rebuke of History: The Southern Agrarians and American Conservative Thought|last=Murphy|first=Paul V.|date=2003|publisher=University of North Carolina Press|page=247}}</ref>''<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\"Kurtz\">[[Howard Kurtz]], [https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1995/10/19/washington-times-clips-its-right-wing/dd009c93-883b-446c-bbbf-94c0a0570a1a/ Washington Times Clips Its Right Wing], ''The Washington Post'', October 19, 1995.</ref>''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/02/23/us/politics-on-the-move-buchanan-drawing-extremist-support-and-problems-too.html|title=Buchanan Drawing Extremist Support, and Problems, Too|last=Frantz|first=Douglas|date=February 23, 1996|work=The New York Times|last2=Janofsky|first2=Michael}}</ref> At the conference, Francis called on whites to \"reassert our identity and our solidarity, and we must do so in explicitly racial terms through the articulation of a racial consciousness as whites... The civilization that we as whites created in Europe and America could not have developed apart from the genetic endowments of the creating people.\"''<ref name=\"Kurtz\" />'' When Francis died in 2005, ''The Washington Times'' wrote a \"glowing\" [[obituary]] that omitted his racist beliefs, as well as his firing from the paper, and described him as a \"scholarly, challenging and sometimes pungent writer\"; in response, editor David Mastio of the conservative ''[[Washington Examiner]]'' wrote in an obituary that \"Sam Francis was merely a racist and doesn\u2019t deserve to be remembered as anything less.\"<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/shots-fired-book-delayed/|title=Shots Fired, Book Delayed|work=AdWeek|date=August 28, 2006}}</ref><ref name=\":17\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dcexaminer.com/articles/2005/02/22/opinion/op-ed/01agoped.txt|title=Francis re-fought immoral battles of 1964|last=Mastio|first=David|work=Washington Examiner|date=February 22, 2005|archive-url=https://archive.today/20181226023344/http://calledasseen.blogspot.com/2005/02/washington-examiner-op-ed-on-sam.html|archive-date=December 26, 2018|access-date=December 26, 2018|url-status = dead|df=}}</ref> Mastio added that Francis \"led a double life {{ndash}} by day he served up conservative, red meat that was strong but never quite out of bounds by mainstream standards; by night, unbeknownst to the ''Times'' or his syndicate, he pushed white supremacist ideas.\"<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":17\" />\n\nThe [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] (SPLC) noted that ''The Washington Times'' had by 2005 published at least 35 articles by Marian Kester Coombs, who was married to managing editor Francis Coombs. She had a record of racially incendiary rhetoric and had written for the white nationalist magazine ''[[The Occidental Quarterly|Occidental Quarterly]]''.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite magazine|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2005/washington-times-editor-and-wife-promote-radical-right-agenda|title=Washington Times Editor and Wife Promote Radical Right Agenda|magazine=Intelligence Report|publisher=Southern Poverty Law Center|authors=Heidi Beirich & Mark Potok|issue=Spring 2005|date=April 28, 2005}}</ref> The SPLC highlighted columns written by Marian Kester Coombs in ''The Washington Times'', in which she asserted that the whole of human history was \"the struggle of ... races\"; that non-white immigration is the \"importing [of] poverty and revolution\" that will end in \"the eventual loss of sovereign American territory\"; and that Muslims in England \"are turning life in this once pleasant land into a misery for its native inhabitants.\"<ref name=\":11\" />\n\nIn 2006, Moon's son [[Hyun Jin Moon]], president and CEO of News World Communications, dismissed managing editor Francis \"Fran\" Coombs because of accusations of racist editorializing. Coombs had made some racist and [[sexism|sexist]] comments, for which he was sued by his colleagues.<ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.thenation.com/article/hell-times/ |title=Hell of a Times |journal=The Nation |accessdate=July 1, 2013|date=September 21, 2006 }}</ref>\n\n==== Coverage of Barack Obama ====\n\nIn 2008, ''The Washington Times'' published a column by Frank Gaffney that promoted the false [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories which asserted that President Barack Obama was born in Kenya]] and was courting the \"jihadist vote.\" Gaffney also published pieces in 2009 and 2010 promoting the false assertion that [[Barack Obama religion conspiracy theories|Obama is a Muslim]].<ref name=\"Obama\"/> In a 2009 column entitled \"'Inner Muslim' at work in Cairo\", Pruden wrote that President Obama was the \"first president without an instinctive appreciation of the culture, history, tradition, common law and literature whence America sprang. The genetic imprint writ large in his 43 predecessors is missing from the Obama DNA.\"<ref name=\":4\" /> In another 2009 column, Pruden wrote that Obama had \"no natural instinct or blood impulse\u201d for what America was about because he was \u201csired by a [[Kenya]]n father\u201d and \u201cborn to a mother attracted to men of the [[Third World]].\"<ref name=\":4\" /> These columns stirred controversy, leading the paper to assign David Mastio, by then the paper's deputy editor, to edit Pruden's work.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nRock musician [[Ted Nugent]], a fervent critic of President Obama, published weekly columns for ''The Washington Times'' between 2010 and 2012.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2014/02/ted-nugent-loses-the-washington-times-rick-perry-rand-paul.html|title=Ted Nugent Loses the Washington Times, Rick Perry, Rand Paul|last=Weigel|first=David|date=February 21, 2014|website=Slate Magazine|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/06/ted-nugent-obama-humanity_n_1747876.html|title=Ted Nugent: 'Obama Represents Everything Bad About Humanity'|last=Gentilviso|first=Chris|date=August 6, 2012|work=Huffington Post|access-date=December 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/post/washington-times-and-its-columnist-ted-nugent/2012/04/18/gIQAPXJKRT_blog.html|title=Washington Times and its columnist, Ted Nugent|last=Wemple|first=Erik|date=2012|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> Prior to joining the ''Times'', Nugent stirred controversy by referring to Obama as a \"piece of shit\" and calling on him \"to suck on my machine gun\",<ref name=\":13\" /><ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/article/2012/04/18/ted-nugents-greatest-hits-his-10-most-outlandish-quotes/|title=Ted Nugent's Greatest Hits|website=EW.com|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref> and had also pleaded fealty to the [[Flags of the Confederate States of America|Confederate flag]].<ref name=\":13\" /> In 2012, Nugent was visited by the Secret Service after he alluded to beheading President Obama.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ted-nugent-confederacy-won-civil-war-john-roberts-346041|title=Ted Nugent Wonders if 'We'd Have Been Better Off if the South Had Won the Civil War'|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\":16\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/19/ted-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-said|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910234929/http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/19/ted-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-saided-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-said.html?source=dictionary|title=Nugent: President Obama Is 'Subhuman Mongrel'|last=Jacobs|first=Ben|date=February 19, 2014|work=The Daily Beast|language=en|archive-date=2015-09-10|url-status=dead}}</ref> He said that if Obama would win re-election, \"I will either be dead or in jail by this time next year.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc7.com/archive/8625185/|title=Ted Nugent to be probed for anti-Obama rant?|last=Heller|first=Corinne|publisher=[[KABC-TV]]|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181226035230/https://abc7.com/archive/8625185/|archive-date=December 26, 2018|url-status = dead}}</ref> At the time, [[Mitt Romney]]'s presidential campaign condemned Nugent's remarks; ''Post'' media critic [[Erik Wemple]] noted that there was no response by ''The Washington Times''.<ref name=\":13\" /> In 2014, Nugent (who had by then departed from the ''Times'') described Obama as a \"subhuman [[mongrel]]\", which is a term for mixed-breed dogs.<ref name=\":12\" /> Pruden condemned Nugent's remarks, describing Nugent as an \"aging rock musician with a loose mouth who was semifamous 40 years ago.\"<ref name=\":12\" /> In response to Pruden's condemnation, [[David Weigel]] remarked in ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', \"That long ago? Only a year ago, he filed a special column for the ''Washington Times''. Before that, for a few years, he published a weekly column.\".<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nIn 2016, ''The Washington Times'' claimed that $3.6 million in federal funds were spent on a 2013 golf outing for President Obama and [[Tiger Woods]]. ''[[Snopes]]'' rated the article \"mostly false\", because the estimated cost included both official business travel and a brief presidential vacation in [[Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.snopes.com/fact-check/obama-golf-outing-with-tiger-woods/|title=FALSE: Obama Golf Outing with Tiger Woods Cost Nearly $4 Million|work=Snopes.com|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==== Anti-Muslim content ====\nGaffney, known for his \"long history of pushing extreme anti-Muslim views\", wrote weekly columns for ''The Washington Times'' from the late 1990s to 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/12/08/donald-trump-frank-gaffney-islamophobia-poll/|title=Meet Donald Trump's Islamophobia Expert|last=Clifton|first=Eli|website=Foreign Policy|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/03/frank-gaffney-donald-trump-and-the-denationalization-of-american-muslims/519954/|title=Frank Gaffney's Campaign to Denationalize American Muslims|last=Beinart|first=Peter|date=March 19, 2017|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref> According to John Esposito, a Professor of Religion and International Affairs and of Islamic Studies at [[Georgetown University]], Gaffney's \"editorial track record in the ''Washington Times'' is long on accusation and short on supportive evidence.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/the-future-of-islam-9780199975778|title=The Future of Islam|last=Esposito|first=John L.|date=June 27, 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199975778|location=Oxford, New York|pages=19}}</ref> In columns for the ''Times'', Gaffney helped to popularize conspiracy theories that Islamic terrorists were infiltrating the Bush administration, the conservative movement and the Obama administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://press.princeton.edu/titles/10395.html|title=Terrified|last=Bail|first=Christopher|date=|website=Princeton University Press|pages=49\u201351, 99|language=en|access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/08/01/frank-gaffney-grover-norquist-muslim-brotherhood_n_1699604.html|title=Frank Gaffney Plotting To Take Down Grover Norquist With Muslim Brotherhood Accusations|last=Terkel|first=Amanda|date=August 1, 2012|work=Huffington Post|access-date=December 25, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2015/12/15/cruz-s-cozy-ties-to-dc-s-most-prominent-paranoid-islamophobe|title=Cruz's Cozy Ties To DC's Most Prominent, Paranoid Islamophobe|last=Woodruff|first=Betsy|date=December 15, 2015|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=December 25, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In 2015, the ''Times'' published a column describing refugees fleeing the [[Syrian Civil War]] as an \"Islamic [[Trojan Horse]]\" conducting a \"'jihad' by another name.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/presidential-campaign/262953-the-paranoid-style-in-islamophobic-politics|title=The paranoid style in Islamophobic politics|last=Picard|first=Joe|date=December 14, 2015|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=December 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/monica-crowley-latest-addition-to-trumps-national-security-team-believes-in-fighting-islam-the-way-we-fought-the-nazis-212132606.html|title=Monica Crowley, latest addition to Trump's national security team, believes in fighting Islam 'the way we fought the Nazis'|website=www.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=December 29, 2018}}</ref> In a column on Islam, Nugent wrote, \"If Islam is the religion of peace, then I\u2019m a malnourished, tofu-eating anti-hunter,\" but did clarify \"not all Muslims are religious whacks who deserve a bullet.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/02/19/ted-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-saided-nugent-s-crazy-slur-toward-pres-and-9-other-awful-things-he-s-said|title=Nugent: President Obama Is 'Subhuman Mongrel'|last=Jacobs|first=Ben|date=February 19, 2014|work=The Daily Beast|access-date=December 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2016 report, the Muslim advocacy group [[Council on American\u2013Islamic Relations|Council on American-Islamic Relations]] listed ''The Washington Times'' among media outlets it said \"regularly demonstrates or supports Islamophobic themes.\"<ref name=\"deseretnews.com\"/> In 1998 the Egyptian newspaper ''[[Al-Ahram]]'' wrote that its {{'}} editorial policy was \"rabidly anti-[[Arab people|Arab]], anti-Muslim and pro-Israel.\"<ref>[http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/1998/403/op1.htm The same old game] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215193404/http://weekly.ahram.org.eg/1998/403/op1.htm|date=February 15, 2009}}, ''[[Al-Ahram]]'', November 12\u201318, 1998, \"The Washington Times is a mouthpiece for the ultra conservative right, unquestioning supporters of Israel's [[Likud]] government. The newspaper is owned by Sun Myung Moon, originally a native of North Korea and head of the Unification Church, whose ultra-right leanings make him a ready ally for Netanyahu. Whether or not Netanyahu is personally acquainted with Moon is unclear, though there is no doubt that he has established close friendships with several staff members on ''The Washington Times'', whose editorial policy is rabidly anti-Arab, anti-Muslim and pro-Israel.\"</ref>\n\n=== Other controversies ===\nSome former employees, including Whelan, have insisted that ''The Washington Times'' was always under Moon's control. Whelan, whose contract guaranteed editorial autonomy, left the paper when the owners refused to renew the contract.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/23/us/ex-publisher-says-moon-church-ran-newspaper.html \"Ex-Publisher Says Moon Church Ran Newspaper\"], [[The New York Times]], Susan Rasky, July 23, 1984. Retrieved June 20, 2014.</ref> Three years later, editorial page editor William P. Cheshire and four of his staff resigned, charging that, at the explicit direction of Sang Kook Han, a top official of the Unification movement, then-[[executive editor]] [[Arnaud de Borchgrave]] had stifled editorial criticism of political repression in South Korea under [[President of South Korea|President]] [[Chun Doo-hwan]].<ref>\"Five Resign from ''Washington Times'',\" ''The Washington Post'', April 15, 1987.</ref> In 1982, ''The Washington Times'' refused to publish film critic Scott Sublett's negative review of the movie ''[[Inchon (film)|Inchon]]'', which was also sponsored by the Unification movement.<ref name=\"romano\">{{cite news |last=Romano |first=Lois |title=Review is Killed |work=[[The Washington Post]] |page=C1  |date=September 18, 1982}}</ref>\n\n''The Washington Times'' reporters visited imprisoned [[South Africa]]n [[civil rights]] activist [[Nelson Mandela]] during the 1980s. Mandela wrote of them in his autobiography ''Long Walk to Freedom'', \"They seemed less intent on finding out my views than on proving that I was a Communist and a terrorist. All of their questions were slanted in that direction, and when I reiterated that I was neither a Communist nor a terrorist, they attempted to show that I was not a Christian either by asserting that the Reverend Martin Luther King never resorted to violence.\"<ref name=\":822\"/><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.littlebrown.com/titles/nelson-mandela/long-walk-to-freedom/9780759521049/|title=Long Walk to Freedom|last=Mandela|first=Nelson|isbn=|location=|pages=315|language=en-US|date=June 27, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, ''The Washington Times'' published a misleading story suggesting that Democratic presidential candidate [[Michael Dukakis]] had sought psychiatric help, and included a quote from Dukakis' sister-in-law saying \"it is possible\" he visited a psychiatrist. However, the paper misleadingly clipped the full quote by the sister-in-law, which was, \"It's possible, but I doubt it.\"<ref name=\":18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1988/08/13/reporter-quits-over-dukakis-story/a20b4aae-a28c-4dff-85d0-e3bd5d359306/|title=REPORTER QUITS OVER DUKAKIS STORY|last=|first=|date=1988|work=The Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref> Reporter Peggy Weyrich quit in 1991 after one of her articles about [[Anita Hill]]'s testimony in the [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nominee hearings]] was rewritten to depict Hill as a \"fantasizer.\"<ref name=\":822\"/>\n\nIn a 1997 column, Frank Gaffney falsely alleged a [[seismic]] incident in [[Russia]] was a nuclear detonation at that nation's [[Novaya Zemlya]] test site, which would have meant that Russia had violated the [[Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty]] (CTB).<ref name=\"bas222\">{{cite news|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vgwAAAAAMBAJ|title=Spinning to the Right|last1=Isaacs|first1=John|date=November 1997|work=[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]|accessdate=July 22, 2016}}</ref> Subsequent scientific analysis of the Novaya Zemlya event showed that it was a routine [[earthquake]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.armscontrol.org/print/357|title=False Accusations, Undetected Tests and Implications for the CTB Treaty|last1=Wallace|first1=Terry|work=[[Arms Control Association]]|accessdate=July 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180523100845/https://www.armscontrol.org/print/357|archive-date=May 23, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Reporting on the allegation, the ''[[Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists]]'' observed that following its publication \"fax machines around Washington, D.C. and across the country poured out pages detailing Russian duplicity. They came from Frank Gaffney.\" The ''Bulletin'' also noted that during the first four months of 1997, Gaffney had \"issued more than 25 screeds\" against the CTB.<ref name=\"bas222\" />\n\nIn 2002, ''The Washington Times'' published a story accusing the [[National Educational Association]] (NEA), the largest teachers' [[Labor union|union]] in the United States, of teaching students that the policies of the U.S. government were partly responsible for the [[9/11|2001 terrorist attacks]] on the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]].<ref name=\":83\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2002/09/05/nea/|title=The big NEA-Sept. 11 lie|date=September 5, 2002|website=Salon|language=en|access-date=December 24, 2018}}</ref>  Brendan Nyhan (now a [[University of Michigan]] political science professor) wrote that the story was a \"lie\" and a \"myth\".<ref name=\":83\" />  The accusation was denied by the NEA.<ref name=\"The Boston Globe, 2002-09-022\">{{cite news|url=http://cathyyoung.net/bgcolumns/2002/unfair.html|title=An unfair attack on teachers union|last=Young|first=Cathy|date=September 2, 2002|work=Boston Globe|accessdate=April 17, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=Letter to ''The Washington Times'' from NEA President|date=August 20, 2002|publisher=[[National Education Association]]|url=http://www.nea.org/nr/nr020820b.html|last=Chase|first=Bob|accessdate=April 17, 2008|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080517134505/http://www.nea.org/nr/nr020820b.html|archivedate=May 17, 2008|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 ''The Washington Times'' published a commentary piece by retired U.S. Navy admiral [[James Lyons (admiral)|James A. Lyons]] which promoted conspiracy theories about the [[murder of Seth Rich]]. In the piece, Lyon said that it was \"well known in intelligence circles that Seth Rich and his brother, Aaron Rich, downloaded the [[Democratic National Committee|DNC]] emails and was paid by [[WikiLeaks]] for that information.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" /> The piece cited no evidence for the assertion.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/local/wp/2018/03/27/brother-of-slain-dnc-staffer-seth-rich-sues-right-wing-activists-newspaper-over-conspiracy-theories/|title=Brother of slain DNC staffer Seth Rich sues right-wing activists, newspaper over conspiracy theories|last=Eltagouri|first=Marwa|date=March 27, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> Aaron Rich filed a lawsuit against ''The Washington Times'', saying that it acted with \"reckless disregard for the truth\" and that it did not retract or remove the piece after \"receiving notice of the falsity of the statements about Aaron after the publication\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/2018/05/21/media/seth-rich-brad-bauman-lawsuit/index.html|title=Former Seth Rich family spokesman files lawsuit against individuals, media outlet he says defamed him|last=Darcy|first=Oliver|work=CNNMoney|access-date=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/380452-brother-of-slain-dnc-staffer-sues-washington-times-conservative-activists|title=Brother of slain DNC staffer sues ''Washington Times'', conservative activists|last=Anapol|first=Avery|date=March 27, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Rich and ''The Washington Times'' settled their lawsuit and the paper issued an \"unusually robust\" retraction.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news |last1=Darcy |first1=Oliver |title=''The Washington Times'' settles lawsuit with Seth Rich's brother, issues retraction and apology for its coverage |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/10/01/media/washington-times-aaron-rich/index.html |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |work=CNNMoney}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Retraction: Aaron Rich and the murder of Seth Rich |url=https://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2018/sep/30/retraction-aaron-rich-and-murder-seth-rich/ |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |work=The Washington Times}}</ref>\n\n==Staff==\n'''Editors-in-chief'''\n\n*[[James R. Whelan]] (1982\u20131984)\n*[[Smith Hempstone]] (1984\u20131986)\n*[[Arnaud de Borchgrave]] (1986\u20131992)\n*[[Wesley Pruden]] (1992\u20132008)\n*[[John F. Solomon]] (2008\u20132009) (2013\u20132015)\n*[[Sam Dealey]] (2010)\n*[[Ed Kelley]] (2011\u20132012)\n* David S. Jackson (2012\u20132013)\n*[[Christopher Dolan]] (2015\u2013present)\n\n'''Managing editors'''\n\n*[[Josette Sheeran Shiner]] (1992\u20131997)\n*Francis Coombs (?\u20132008)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/digital/times-says-goodbye-to-pruden-coombs/|title=Times Says Goodbye To Pruden, Coombs|website=AdWeek|date=January 28, 2008}}</ref>\n\n'''Opinion editors'''\n\n*[[Ann Crutcher]] (1984\u20131985)\n*[[William P. Cheshire]] (1985\u20131987)\n*[[Tony Snow]] (1987\u20131990)\n*[[Tod Lindberg]] (1991\u20131998)\n*[[Tony Blankley]] (2002\u20132007)\n*[[Richard Miniter]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/11/17/AR2009111703325.html|title=Washington Times editor Richard Miniter files discrimination claim|last=Kurtz|first=Howard|date=November 17, 2009|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref> (2009)\n*[[Brett Decker]] (2009\u20132013)\n*[[Wesley Pruden]] (2013)\n*[[David Keene]] (2014\u20132016)\n*[[Charles Hurt]] (2016\u2013present)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/dec/18/charles-hurt-rejoins-the-washington-times-as-new-o/|title=Charles Hurt rejoins The Washington Times as new opinion editor|work=The Washington Times|date=December 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n'''Current contributors'''{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Wesley Pruden]] (editor emeritus and opinion columnist)\n*[[Bill Gertz]] (\"Inside the Ring\" columnist)\n*[[Rowan Scarborough]] (national security writer)\n*[[Donald Lambro]] (chief political correspondent)\n*[[Jennifer Harper]] (\"Inside the Beltway\" columnist)\n*[[Joseph Curl]] (writer and columnist)\n*[[Victor Davis Hanson]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Thom Loverro]] (sports columnist)\n*[[Mark Kellner]] (religion columnist)\n*[[Rita Cook]] (automobile columnist)\n*[[Newt Gingrich]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Jenny Beth Martin]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Richard W. Rahn]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Emmett Tyrrell|R. Emmett Tyrrell, Jr.]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Clifford D. May]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Cal Thomas]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Robert H. Knight]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Peter Morici]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Tammy Bruce]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Charles Hurt]] (opinion editor and columnist)\n*[[Jeffrey Birnbaum]] (columnist)\n*[[Stephen Moore (writer)|Stephen Moore]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Ed Feulner]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Foster Friess]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Allen West (politician)|Allen West]] (opinion columnist){{div col end}}\n\n'''Former contributors'''{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[George Archibald (journalist)|George Archibald]] (congressional, political, United Nations, and education reporter)\n*[[Bruce Bartlett]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[David Brooks (journalist)|David Brooks]] (editorial writer, film reviewer)\n*[[Amanda Carpenter]] (columnist)\n*[[Ben Carson]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Monica Crowley]] (online opinion editor and columnist)\n*[[Dave Fay]] (editor and journalists, deceased)\n*[[Bruce Fein]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Samuel T. Francis]] (editor and columnist, deceased)\n*[[Frank Gaffney]] (columnist)\n*[[Madison Gesiotto]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Michael Hayden (general)|Michael Hayden]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Nat Hentoff]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Shirley A. Husar]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Ernest Istook]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Drew Johnson]] (columnist)\n*[[Tom Knott]] (sports columnist)\n*[[Lawrence Kudlow]] (economics columnist)\n*[[Jeffrey T. Kuhner|Jeffrey Kuhner]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Willie Lawson]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Tod Lindberg]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Herbert London]] (opinion columnist) (deceased)\n*[[Michelle Malkin]] (columnist)\n*[[John McCaslin]] (\"Inside the Beltway\" columnist)\n*[[Oliver North]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Ted Nugent]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Rand Paul]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/feb/8/sen-rand-paul-trust-verify-immigration-reform/ |title=Sen. Rand Paul: Trust but verify on immigration reform |work=The Washington Times |date=February 8, 2013 |accessdate=July 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/nov/5/washington-times-ends-sen-rand-paul-column-amid-pl/ |title=Washington Times ends Sen. Rand Paul column amid plagiarism allegations |work=The Washington Times |date=November 5, 2013 |accessdate=November 5, 2013}}</ref> (opinion columnist)\n*[[Jeremiah O'Leary]] (deceased)\n*[[John Podhoretz]] (columnist)\n*Fred Reed (journalist)\n*[[Rob Redding]] (journalist and talk host)\n*[[Kelly Riddell]] (\"Water Cooler\" columnist)\n*[[James S. Robbins]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Bill Sammon]] (White House correspondent)\n*[[Mercedes Schlapp]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Thomas Sowell]] (columnist)\n*[[Mark Steyn]] (opinion columnist)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/article/20080407/COMMENTARY08/963463285/1012 |title=Closing time at Cafe Clinton? \u2013 - Breaking News, Political News & National Security News \u2013 The Washington Times |date=April 11, 2008 |access-date=June 21, 2016 |url-status = unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411170458/http://www.washingtontimes.com/article/20080407/COMMENTARY08/963463285/1012 |archivedate=April 11, 2008 }}</ref>\n*[[Janine Turner]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Harlan K. Ullman|Harlan Ullman]] (opinion columnist)\n*[[Diana West]] (opinion columnist)\n{{div col end}}\n'''Others'''\n* [[Daniel Wattenberg]]: Arts and Entertainment editor\n* [[Julia Duin]]: Religion editor\n{{inc-lit}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Journalism}}\n* [[Media in Washington, D.C.]], [[List of newspapers in Washington, D.C.]]\n* ''[[The Washington Star]]'' (1852\u20131981)\n* ''[[The Washington Post]]'' (1877\u2013present)\n* ''[[Washington Times-Herald]]'', a former D.C. daily newspaper founded by [[William Randolph Hearst]] as ''The Evening Times''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026749/ |title=About ''The Washington Times'' (Washington {{bracket|D.C.}}) 1902\u20131939 |work=Chronicling America |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130235120/http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84026749/ |archive-date=January 30, 2016 |url-status = live|publisher=Library of Congress |location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref>\n* [[Washington Times-Herald (Indiana)|''Washington Times-Herald'']], a [[Washington, Indiana]] newspaper\n* [[Unification Church political activities]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Washington Times}}\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{White House James S. Brady Press Briefing Room Seating Chart}}\n{{Unification Church}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Washington Times, The}}\n[[Category:1982 establishments in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Conservative media in the United States]]\n[[Category:National newspapers published in the United States]]\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Unification Church affiliated organizations]]\n[[Category:Politics of climate change]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8807:2300:293:7591:2564:695b:f1b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Washington_Times"}
{"title_page": "Sanusi Ado Bayero", "text_new": "{{short description|member of the Kano royal family (b. 1956)}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=July 2013}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|name=Sanusi Ado Bayero|image=|spouse=|issue=|father=[[Ado Bayero]]|mother=|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1956|04|1|df=y}}|birth_place=[[Kano]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]],<br>[[British Nigeria]]|death_date=|death_place=|religion=[[Sunni Islam ]]|full name=Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero|house=[[Ibrahim Dabo|Dabo]]|title=[[Shura/ Taran Kano|Chiroma of Kano]]}}\n\n'''Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero''' (born 1 April 1956) was the [[Shura/ Taran Kano|Chiroma]] of [[Kano Emirate Council|Kano]] from 1990 to 2015.<ref name=cable>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/the-lovable-prince-who-lost-to-sanusi|title=The amiable Prince Bayero who lost to Sanusi|date=2014-06-09|website=TheCable|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\n\n=== Family ===\nSanusi Lamido Ado Bayero was born on 1 April 1956, during the reign of his uncle Emir [[Muhammadu Sanusi I]]. His father, [[Ado Bayero]], was the brother of the Emir, and later became [[Emir of Kano]] from 1963 to 2014. He is the eldest son and first child of his father; his mother was his fathers cousin. He was born at his father's house: Filin [[Charanchi|Chiranchi]] (Chiranchi Field), where his father stayed before becoming the Emir of Kano. Sanusi Ado later made the house his official residence in Kano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yasirramadangwale.blogspot.com/2014/06/chiroman-kano-alhaji-sunusi-lamido-ado.html|title=In zaka Fadi, Fadi Gaskiya Komai Taka Jamaka...: Chiroman Kano: Alhaji Sunusi Lamido Ado Bayero|last=Gwale|first=Yasir Ramadan|date=2014-06-11|website=In zaka Fadi, Fadi Gaskiya Komai Taka Jamaka...|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\nSanusi Ado is the eldest [[primogeniture]] of the royal family, and is revered by the emirate and people. His younger siblings include current Emir of Kano: [[Aminu Ado Bayero]] and Alhaji Nasiru Bayero the Emir of Bichi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prnigeria.com/2020/03/09/aminu-nasiru-emirs-kano/|title=Bayero's Sons, Aminu and Nasiru Become Emirs of Two Emirates in Kano|last=PRNigeria|date=2020-03-09|website=PRNigeria News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> His cousin, [[Sanusi Lamido Sanusi|Muhammadu Sanusi II]] (Sanusi Lamido Sanusi) succeeded his father as Emir of Kano from 2014 to 2020, when he was dethroned by the state government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51804764|title=Nigeria's revered emir dethroned for 'disrespect'|date=2020-03-09|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-23|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nSanusi Ado received his primary education at the Rano Boarding Primary School from 1963 to 1969. He attended Rumfa College in Kano from 1969 to 1973, before later attending [[Government College, Birnin Kudu]], one of the oldest prestigious government colleges in [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Nigeria]] from 1973 to 1975, where he was the head boy. He attended the Nigerian College of Arts, Science and Technology in [[Zaria]] from 1975 to 1976.<ref name=cable />\n\nIn 1976, he proceeded to the Ecole International De La Langue Francoise in [[Paris]], where he received a French diploma in 1979. He then proceeded to [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]], where he received a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[law]] in 1983, and was called to the [[Nigerian Bar Association|Nigerian Bar]] in 1984. After his call to the bar, he served his mandatory [[National Youth Service Corps|youth service]] as a lecturer at the [[Kaduna Polytechnic]] from 1984 to 1985.<ref name=cable />\n\n== Early career ==\nA highly capable administrator, Sanusi Ado served in the Kano State Ministry of Justice as a state counsel from 1985 to 1987, before becoming legal adviser and company secretary of Kano State Investment and Properties between 1988 and 1989. In 1986, he founded a private practice Lamido & Co. in Kano. He was the director general of the Kano State Council of Chiefs from 1991 to 1993, and was later transferred to be the head of Special Duties of the Kano State Government between 1993 and 1996. Between 1996 and 2000, he was the permanent secretary of the Ministry of Information, Youth and Culture. In April 2015, he was appointed the managing director of the [[Nigerian Ports Authority|Nigerian Port Authority]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shipsandports.com.ng/profile-of-the-new-md-of-npa-sanusi-lamido-ado-bayero/|title=Profile of the new MD of NPA, Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero|last=Ships & Ports|date=2015-05-04|website=Ships & Ports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>, he position he held until his removal in August 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2015/08/13/buhari-sacks-npa-boss-ado-bayero/|title=Buhari sacks NPA boss, Ado Bayero - P.M. News|website=www.pmnewsnigeria.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Crown prince ==\nIn 1990, Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero was crowned the [[Shura/ Taran Kano|Chiroma]] of [[Kano Emirate Council|Kano]] (Crown Prince), member of the [[Kano Emirate Council]] and District Head of [[Gwale]] by Emir Ado Bayero.\n\n=== Succession ===\nIn 2014, after fifty-one years on the throne his father, Ado Bayero died.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nigeria-emir-idUSKBN0EH0YM20140606|title=Nigeria's second highest Islamic traditional monarch dies|date=2014-06-06|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-23|language=en}}</ref> A bitter succession struggle over who'd succeed him emerged within the royal family between the Bayero and Sanusi houses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2014/06/succession-war-ex-cbn-governor-uncle-tight-race-emir-kano/|title=Succession war: Ex-CBN governor, uncle in tight race for the Emir of Kano|date=2014-06-07|website=Vanguard News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> As his eldest son and heir, Sanusi Ado was considered the natural successor and initial reports announced him as Emir.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenigerianvoice.com/news/148932/first-son-of-late-ado-bayero-ciroman-kano-emerges-new-emir.html|title=First Son Of Late Ado Bayero, Ciroman Kano, Emerges New Emir|website=Nigerian Voice|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> On 8 June 2014, his cousin [[Sanusi Lamido Sanusi]] was crowned Emir of Kano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/breaking-sls-named-new-emir-of-kano|title=SLS named new emir of Kano|date=2014-06-08|website=TheCable|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> Sanusi Ado in protest decided to leave Kano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eagleyereportconnect.blogspot.com/2014/06/eldest-son-of-late-emir-of-kano-alhaji.html|title=E.E.R: Eldest son of late Emir of Kano, Alhaji Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero Leaves Kano State.|last=Veracity|first=The Eagle Eye|date=2014-06-19|website=E.E.R|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> In 2015, he was stripped of all his titles, after refusing to pay allegiance to Emir Sanusi Lamido Sanusi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsnigeria.com.ng/2015/10/28/emir-sanusi-sacks-bayero-rival-for-throne/|title=Emir Sanusi sacks Bayero, rival for throne -|date=2015-10-28|website=The NEWS|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSanusi Ado speaks fluent [[Arabic]], [[Hausa language|Hausa]], [[English language|English]] and [[French language|French]]. And he enjoys playing [[Squash (sport)|squash]], [[reading]], [[travelling]], [[farming]] and [[Horse Riding|horse-riding]].<ref name=cable />\n\n== Titles, styles and memberships ==\n\n=== Titles and styles ===\n\n* From 1956 to 1990 - Various titles including: Dan Ruwatan Kano, Tafidan Kano, Sarikin Dawakin Tsakargida ([[Master of the Horse]] of the [[Gidan Rumfa|Inner House]])\n* 1990 \u2013 2015 - Chiroma of Kano (Crown Prince of Kano)\n\n=== Memberships ===\n\n* In 1995, he became the Chairman of [[Ancient Kano City Walls|City Walls and Gates]]\n* Member of the Inter-Faith Conference Fez, Morocco\n* Member of the board of several companies, organizations and NGOs\n* Member of the Doha Conference on Inter-Cultural and Civilization Dialogue\n* Member of the Task Force of the Next Generation Nigeria initiative by the [[British Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nextgenerationnigeria.org/|title=Next Generation Nigeria|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n[[Category:Politics of Kano]]\n[[Category:Nigerian politicians]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|member of the Kano royal family (b. 1956)}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=July 2013}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox royalty|name=Sanusi Ado Bayero|image=|spouse=|issue=|father=[[Ado Bayero]]|mother=|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1956|04|1|df=y}}|birth_place=[[Kano]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]],<br>[[British Nigeria]]|death_date=|death_place=|religion=[[Sunni Islam ]]|full name=Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero|house=[[Ibrahim Dabo|Dabo]]|title=[[Shura/ Taran Kano|Chiroma of Kano]]}}\n\n'''Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero''' (born 1 April 1956) was the [[Shura/ Taran Kano|Chiroma]] of [[Kano Emirate Council|Kano]] from 1990 to 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/the-lovable-prince-who-lost-to-sanusi|title=The amiable Prince Bayero who lost to Sanusi|date=2014-06-09|website=TheCable|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\n\n=== Family ===\nSanusi Lamido Ado Bayero was born on 1 April 1956, during the reign of his uncle Emir [[Muhammadu Sanusi I]]. His father, [[Ado Bayero]], was the brother of the Emir, and later became [[Emir of Kano]] from 1963 to 2014. He is the eldest son and first child of his father; his mother was his fathers cousin. He was born at his father's house: Filin [[Charanchi|Chiranchi]] (Chiranchi Field), where his father stayed before becoming the Emir of Kano. Sanusi Ado later made the house his official residence in Kano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://yasirramadangwale.blogspot.com/2014/06/chiroman-kano-alhaji-sunusi-lamido-ado.html|title=In zaka Fadi, Fadi Gaskiya Komai Taka Jamaka...: Chiroman Kano: Alhaji Sunusi Lamido Ado Bayero|last=Gwale|first=Yasir Ramadan|date=2014-06-11|website=In zaka Fadi, Fadi Gaskiya Komai Taka Jamaka...|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\nSanusi Ado is the eldest [[primogeniture]] of the royal family, and is revered by the emirate and people. His younger siblings include current Emir of Kano: [[Aminu Ado Bayero]] and Alhaji Nasiru Bayero the Emir of Bichi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://prnigeria.com/2020/03/09/aminu-nasiru-emirs-kano/|title=Bayero's Sons, Aminu and Nasiru Become Emirs of Two Emirates in Kano|last=PRNigeria|date=2020-03-09|website=PRNigeria News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> His cousin, [[Sanusi Lamido Sanusi|Muhammadu Sanusi II]] (Sanusi Lamido Sanusi) succeeded his father as Emir of Kano from 2014 to 2020, when he was dethroned by the state government.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-51804764|title=Nigeria's revered emir dethroned for 'disrespect'|date=2020-03-09|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-23|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n=== Education ===\nSanusi Ado received his primary education at the Rano Boarding Primary School from 1963 to 1969. He attended Rumfa College in Kano from 1969 to 1973, before later attending [[Government College, Birnin Kudu]], one of the oldest prestigious government colleges in [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Nigeria]] from 1973 to 1975, where he was the head boy. He attended the Nigerian College of Arts, Science and Technology in [[Zaria]] from 1975 to 1976.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/the-lovable-prince-who-lost-to-sanusi|title=The amiable Prince Bayero who lost to Sanusi|date=2014-06-09|website=TheCable|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> \n\nIn 1976, he proceeded to the Ecole International De La Langue Francoise in [[Paris]], where he received a French diploma in 1979. He then proceeded to [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]], where he received a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[law]] in 1983, and was called to the [[Nigerian Bar Association|Nigerian Bar]] in 1984. After his call to the bar, he served his mandatory [[National Youth Service Corps|youth service]] as a lecturer at the [[Kaduna Polytechnic]] from 1984 to 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/the-lovable-prince-who-lost-to-sanusi|title=The amiable Prince Bayero who lost to Sanusi|date=2014-06-09|website=TheCable|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Early career ==\nA highly capable administrator, Sanusi Ado served in the Kano State Ministry of Justice as a state counsel from 1985 to 1987, before becoming legal adviser and company secretary of Kano State Investment and Properties between 1988 and 1989. In 1986, he founded a private practice Lamido & Co. in Kano. He was the director general of the Kano State Council of Chiefs from 1991 to 1993, and was later transferred to be the head of Special Duties of the Kano State Government between 1993 and 1996. Between 1996 and 2000, he was the permanent secretary of the Ministry of Information, Youth and Culture. In April 2015, he was appointed the managing director of the [[Nigerian Ports Authority|Nigerian Port Authority]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shipsandports.com.ng/profile-of-the-new-md-of-npa-sanusi-lamido-ado-bayero/|title=Profile of the new MD of NPA, Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero|last=Ships & Ports|date=2015-05-04|website=Ships & Ports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>, he position he held until his removal in August 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pmnewsnigeria.com/2015/08/13/buhari-sacks-npa-boss-ado-bayero/|title=Buhari sacks NPA boss, Ado Bayero - P.M. News|website=www.pmnewsnigeria.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Crown prince ==\nIn 1990, Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero was crowned the [[Shura/ Taran Kano|Chiroma]] of [[Kano Emirate Council|Kano]] (Crown Prince), member of the [[Kano Emirate Council]] and District Head of [[Gwale]] by Emir Ado Bayero.\n\n=== Succession ===\nIn 2014, after fifty-one years on the throne his father, Ado Bayero died.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nigeria-emir-idUSKBN0EH0YM20140606|title=Nigeria's second highest Islamic traditional monarch dies|date=2014-06-06|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-04-23|language=en}}</ref> A bitter succession struggle over who'd succeed him emerged within the royal family between the Bayero and Sanusi houses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2014/06/succession-war-ex-cbn-governor-uncle-tight-race-emir-kano/|title=Succession war: Ex-CBN governor, uncle in tight race for the Emir of Kano|date=2014-06-07|website=Vanguard News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> As his eldest son and heir, Sanusi Ado was considered the natural successor and initial reports announced him as Emir.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenigerianvoice.com/news/148932/first-son-of-late-ado-bayero-ciroman-kano-emerges-new-emir.html|title=First Son Of Late Ado Bayero, Ciroman Kano, Emerges New Emir|website=Nigerian Voice|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> On 8 June 2014, his cousin [[Sanusi Lamido Sanusi]] was crowned Emir of Kano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/breaking-sls-named-new-emir-of-kano|title=SLS named new emir of Kano|date=2014-06-08|website=TheCable|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> Sanusi Ado in protest decided to leave Kano.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eagleyereportconnect.blogspot.com/2014/06/eldest-son-of-late-emir-of-kano-alhaji.html|title=E.E.R: Eldest son of late Emir of Kano, Alhaji Sanusi Lamido Ado Bayero Leaves Kano State.|last=Veracity|first=The Eagle Eye|date=2014-06-19|website=E.E.R|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> In 2015, he was stripped of all his titles, after refusing to pay allegiance to Emir Sanusi Lamido Sanusi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsnigeria.com.ng/2015/10/28/emir-sanusi-sacks-bayero-rival-for-throne/|title=Emir Sanusi sacks Bayero, rival for throne -|date=2015-10-28|website=The NEWS|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSanusi Ado speaks fluent [[Arabic]], [[Hausa language|Hausa]], [[English language|English]] and [[French language|French]]. And he enjoys playing [[Squash (sport)|squash]], [[reading]], [[travelling]], [[farming]] and [[Horse Riding|horse-riding]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecable.ng/the-lovable-prince-who-lost-to-sanusi|title=The amiable Prince Bayero who lost to Sanusi|date=2014-06-09|website=TheCable|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== Titles, styles and memberships ==\n\n=== Titles and styles ===\n\n* From 1956 to 1990 - Various titles including: Dan Ruwatan Kano, Tafidan Kano, Sarikin Dawakin Tsakargida ([[Master of the Horse]] of the [[Gidan Rumfa|Inner House]])\n* 1990 \u2013 2015 - Chiroma of Kano (Crown Prince of Kano)\n\n=== Memberships ===\n\n* In 1995, he became the Chairman of [[Ancient Kano City Walls|City Walls and Gates]]\n* Member of the Inter-Faith Conference Fez, Morocco\n* Member of the board of several companies, organizations and NGOs\n* Member of the Doha Conference on Inter-Cultural and Civilization Dialogue\n* Member of the Task Force of the Next Generation Nigeria initiative by the [[British Council]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nextgenerationnigeria.org/|title=Next Generation Nigeria|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n\n[[Category:Politics of Kano]]\n[[Category:Nigerian politicians]]\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n", "name_user": "Bbarmadillo", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed references duplication", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanusi_Ado_Bayero"}
{"title_page": "Olga Sapphire", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Olga Sapphire\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = Olga Ivanova Pavlova\n| native_name   = Midori Shimizu\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1907|06|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russian Empire]]\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|1981|06|20|1907|06|28|df=y}}\n| death_place   = [[Tokyo]], Japan\n| nationality   = Russian <br/> Japanese\n| other_names   = Midori Aoyama, Origa Shimizu\n| occupation    = ballerina, choreographer, dance instructor\n| years_active  = 1928\u20131980\n| known_for     = Introducing the pedagogy of classical Russian dance to Japan\n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Olga Sapphire''' ('''{{lang-ru|\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430 \u0421\u0430\u0444\u0430\u0439\u044f}}''' or '''{{lang-ru|\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430 \u0421\u0430\u043f\u0444\u0438\u0440}}''', '''{{lang-ja|\u30aa\u30ea\u30ac\u30fb\u30b5\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30a2}}''', 28 June 1907\u201320 June 1981) was the stage name of Russian and Japanese ballerina and choreographer '''Olga Ivanovna Pavlova''' ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430 \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u041f\u0430\u0432\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0430}}), whose married name was '''Midori Shimizu''' ({{lang-ja|\u6e05\u6c34\u307f\u3069\u308a}}). She was classically trained attending both the [[Vaganova Academy of Russian Ballet|Leningrad State Choreographic Institute]] and [[Moscow State Academy of Choreography|Moscow Choreographic School]]. She performed in Russia until her marriage in the early 1930s to a Japanese diplomat. After agreeing to move to Japan in 1936, she developed classical ballet in the country, bringing with her the theoretical and pedagogical materials to underpin her dance lessons and establish the field.\n\nFrom 1936 to her retirement in 1957, Sapphire was employed by the Nihon Gekij\u014d variety theater, serving as its [[prima ballerina]], choreographer and ballet instructor. She performed classic Russian ballets producing all aspects of the productions, as well as choreographing Japanese dances for stage and film. She retired from the stage in 1953, but continued to be influential in ballet until 1957. In 1960, her husband was assigned to a post in Poland and she lived there for three years. In her later years, Sapphire wrote three books about ballet, which remain influential in Japan.\n\n==Early life and training==\nOlga Ivanova Pavlova was born on 28 June 1907 in [[Saint Petersburg]], Russia to Juliana Kuzminichna Kuzmina and Gustav Yanovich Grudberg. Her parents had a [[common-law marriage]], as they were unable to marry since Grudberg was not a member of the [[Russian Orthodox Church]]. He was a locksmith, originally from [[Riga]] and her mother was originally from [[Pskov]], near the [[Estonia]]n border. When their first child, Ekaterina was born, she was baptized with the surname Pavlova, a family name of her great-uncle. When Olga was born, she was given the same surname.{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=253}} The era of her birth was a turbulent time, as the [[1905 Russian Revolution]] had begun two years prior to her birth, [[World War I]] would follow when she was seven years old, and the [[Russian Revolution|1917 Revolution]] began when she was ten.{{sfn|Ascher|1994|p=93}}{{sfn|Sato|1996|p=22}} She later wrote of her childhood that it was a time of cold and hunger.{{sfn|Sato|1996|p=22}}\n\nFrom an early age, Pavlova was taken with ballet, but given their circumstances life as an artist was improbable. When World War I broke out, her mother began working in the store of the [[People's House]], the center of the cultural scene in Saint Petersburg. Against her husband's wishes, Kuzmina encouraged her daughter and at age 12, Pavlova entered the free school located at #3 Gagarinskaya Street.{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=253}} The school was run by Baron Yuri Nikolaevich Miklos, who had opened it as a philanthropic effort to develop dance. He hired noted instructors to teach classical ballet, as well as [[ballroom dancing|ballroom]] and [[character dancing]], and students received 4 years of lectures before their final examinations.{{sfn|\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0443\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0430|1995|pp=2\u20133}} Pavlova studied under Apollinaria Gordova and was classmates with [[Igor Shvetsov]].{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=253}} In 1922, when authorities closed the Miklos school,{{sfn|\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0443\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0430|1995|p=3}} she transferred to the school operated by [[Akim Volynsky]] and studied theory, taking evening dance courses at the [[Vaganova Academy of Russian Ballet|Leningrad State Choreographic Institute]].{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=253}} The [[Stalinism|Stalinist period]] was difficult as classical ballets were being replaced with ideological themes and ballet masters were relocating to the west.{{sfn|Sato|1996|p=22}}  At her 1928 graduation, Pavlova performed as a soloist in fragments choreographed by [[Marius Petipa]] from ''[[La vestale (Spontini)|La vestale]]'' by [[Gaspare Spontini]].{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=253}}\n\n==Career==\n===In Russia (1928\u20131935)===\nPavlova danced with [[Vakhtang Chabukiani]] and {{ill|Sergey Gavrilovich Koren|ru|\u041a\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d\u044c, \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0435\u0439 \u0413\u0430\u0432\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447}} in scenes of the ballet ''The Masque of the Red Death'' ({{lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0421\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438}}) by [[Nikolai Tcherepnin]], on 10 November 1928. The following spring, she joined a dance troupe which traveled to [[Russian Turkestan]], performing at [[Tashkent]],{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=253}} before being invited to dance as a soloist in the theater operated by {{ill|Alexey Feona|ru|\u0424\u0435\u043e\u043d\u0430, \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u041d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447}}.{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=254}} Along with other evening students from the Choreographic Institute, she performed at the [[Mikhailovsky Theatre|Maly Opera House]] and was invited to participate in a touring company that traveled all over Russia between 1931 and 1932. She danced the lead role of Ta\u00ef-Choa in ''[[The Red Poppy]]'' to the music of [[Reinhold Gli\u00e8re]] on the tour.{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|pp=254\u2013255}} In September 1932, she returned to [[Leningrad]] where she lived with her husband, the choreographer of the Khabarovsk Regional Musical Comedy Theater, Leonid Romanovich Leonidov. Theirs was an artistic union, and he staged ''The Red Poppy'' at the theater that year. The marriage failed{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=256}} and Pavlova then married the Japanese diplomat, Takehisa Shimizu, taking the name Midori Shimizu.{{sfn|Japan Ballet Association|2016}}{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009d}} On 13 December 1934, Pavlova moved to Moscow, where she lived at 42 Herzen Street, the location of the Japanese Embassy.{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=256}}\n\nIn Moscow, Pavlova began studying with [[Viktor Aleksandrovich Semenov|Viktor Semenov]]{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=256}} ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0451\u043d\u043e\u0432}}), head of the [[Moscow State Academy of Choreography|Moscow Choreographic School]] between 1931 and 1936.{{sfn|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432|1997}} The repertoire they prepared for her included ''Waltz'' by [[Fritz Kreisler]], ''[[The Dying Swan]]'' by [[Mikhail Fokine]], the role of ''Nikiya'' from [[La Bayad\u00e8re]] by [[Marius Petipa]] and [[Ludwig Minkus]], the part of ''Anitra'' from ''[[Peer Gynt (Grieg)|Peer Gynt]]'' by [[Edvard Grieg]] and excerpts from ''[[Don Quixote (ballet)|Don Quixote]]'' to music by Minkus. Her mixed marriage caused difficulties and the fear of reprisal, as it was typical for people in this period to be accused of [[Espionage|spying]].{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=256}} As Shimizu was a diplomat, he may have had some warning that the [[Great Purge]] was coming.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009d}} They began planning for a move to Japan and Pavlova gathered dance-related books, music, and costumes. She spoke with the Japanese ambassador, who set up a meeting in Moscow with the industrialist [[Ichiz\u014d Kobayashi]], who had opened a theater in Tokyo to run films for audiences of up to 3,000 spectators, which would be suitable to stage a ballet.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009d}}{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=257}} He asked her to come to Japan to establish ballet in the country.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2016}}\n\n===In Japan (1936\u20131980)===\nOn 27 December 1935 Pavlova received her Japanese passport, the following April, Pavlova and Shimizu moved to Tokyo.{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=256}} Pavlova worked with {{ill|Toyokichi Hata|ja|\u79e6\u8c4a\u5409}}, director of Kobayashi's theater to prepare for the first production of ''[[Danse des petits cygnes|Dance of the Little Swans]]'' from ''[[Swan Lake]]''. The audience did not understand the production, which was perceived as a foreign [[jazz dance]]. It would be two years later, when Hata traveled abroad and saw a performance of ''Swan Lake'' in New York City, that he came to appreciate the performance Pavlova had choreographed.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009e}}{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=258}} Pavlova recognized that if she wanted to teach or dance, she would have to become the producer and handle all aspects of the performance, including choreography, costumes, dance training, lighting, music selection, staging, and other things, while learning about the language and culture of Japan.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009e}} She served as the ballet instructor for the {{ill|Nichigeki Dancing Team|ja|\u65e5\u5287\u30c0\u30f3\u30b7\u30f3\u30b0\u30c1\u30fc\u30e0}},{{sfn|''Ballet Today''|1970|p=18}} and was employed by the {{ill|Nippon Gekijo Theatre|lt=Nihon Gekij\u014d|WD=Q35134737}} variety theater.{{sfn|Monden|2014|p=258}}\n\nHer premiere as Midori Aoyama, in Japan, occurred at the [[Takarazuka Theater]] on 12 October 1936, where she danced eight numbers for publicity. After this performance, she began using the stage name Olga Sapphire, to keep her connection to Russia.{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|pp=258\u2013259}} She partnered with {{ill|Azuma Yusaku|ja|\u6771\u52c7\u4f5c}}, who had been trained by {{ill|Eliana Pavlova|ru|\u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u0430, \u042d\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043e}}{{#tag:ref|The first Russian woman to teach social dancing and open a ballet school in Japan was Eliana Pavlova, who arrived in the country in 1919.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009b}} She had not been classically trained,{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009k}} nor was she \"fully qualified [as a] ballet instructor\".{{sfn|Kenji|1998|p=588}} Her area of focus was the production of ballet for the stage and popularizing ballet, rather teaching the theory and tradition behind Russian classical ballet.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009k}}|group=\"Notes\"}} and between 1936 and 1938, they performed at the Nihon Gekij\u014d.{{sfn|Kenji|1998|p=589}} She was the only Western performer at the Nihon Gekijo at the time and served as its [[prima ballerina]], as well as choreographer and teacher. Besides classical Russian ballet, Sapphire choreographed Japanese dances. In 1938, she created and directed ''Impressions of the Orient'' ({{lang-ja|T\u014dy\u014d no insh\u014d}}), a two-act production. She continued to dance classical ballet regularly at the Nehon Gekijo throughout the [[Pacific War]],{{sfn|Koshiro|2013|p=74}} though almost all other theatrical performances had been suspended.{{sfn|Kenji|1998|p=589}} In 1942, she performed the lead role in ''[[Scheherazade (Rimsky-Korsakov)|Scheherazade]]'' to a sold out house at the Takarazuka Theater and in 1943, she performed in the ''Burmese Peacock''.{{sfn|Koshiro|2013|p=74}}\n\nIn addition to working on stage, Sapphire became involved in creating dance scenes in film. Director [[Masahiro Makino]]'s 1943 remake of ''[[Orphans of the Storm]]'', called ''[[Ahen senso]]'' (''Opium War'') featured her choreography. After the war, Kobayashi faced reprisals for his war activities, and Sapphire lost her primary backer. She left the Takarazuka Theater but continued to stage productoions, such as her version of ''[[Carmen (ballet)|Carmen]]'' using a musical arrangement by Shiro Matsumoto, a shortened version of Swan Lake, and scenes from ''[[The Nutcracker]]''. Her last performance was in 1953, though she continued working to promote Japanese ballet until 1957.{{sfn|\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438|\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430|2019|p=260}} In 1960, Sapphire accompanied her husband to a diplomatic post in Poland for three years, before returning to Japan.{{sfn|\u65e5\u5916\u30a2\u30bd\u30b7\u30a8\u30fc\u30c4|2004}}\n\n==Death and legacy==\nSapphire died in Tokyo on 20 June 1981.{{sfn|\u65e5\u5916\u30a2\u30bd\u30b7\u30a8\u30fc\u30c4|2004}} She published three books that were influential on the growth of ballet in Japan,{{sfn|Japan Ballet Association|2016}} as she documented both methods as well as the struggles she had to introduce ballet in a culturally sensitive way so that it could be understood.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009e}} Among her students were {{ill|Akemi Matsuo|ja|\u677e\u5c3e\u660e\u7f8e}}, Junko Matsuyama, and {{ill|Momoko Tani|ja|\u8c37\u6843\u5b50 (\u30d0\u30ec\u30a8\u30c0\u30f3\u30b5\u30fc)}}.{{sfn|Japan Ballet Association|2016}} Her last student, Toshiko Sato published a book about Saphhire's life in 1987 and annually hosted events in her honor for many years.{{sfn|\u65e5\u5916\u30a2\u30bd\u30b7\u30a8\u30fc\u30c4|2004}} In 2001 and again in 2016, Chacott, an international firm selling ballet equipment, hosted an exhibit of artifacts belonging to Sapphire.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009d}} These included a complete collection of [[Leo Tolstoy]]'s works and other literary books, a collection of materials related to dance history and pedagogy, and sheet music, which after 1936 was unable to be exported.{{sfn|\u95a2\u53e3|2009g}}\n\n==Selected works==\n*{{cite book |last=\u30b5\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30a2\u8457 |first=\u30aa\u30ea\u30ac |title=\u30d0\u30ec\u30a8\u3092\u5fd7\u3059\u82e5\u3044\u4eba\u305f\u3061\u3078: \u2015\u3042\u308f\u305b\u3066\u3001\u305d\u306e\u4e21\u89aa\u306e\u65b9\u305f\u3061\u3078\u2015 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VkcjbmGJVscC&pg=PA254 |edition=Tokyo |year=1980 |publisher=\u971e\u30f6\u95a2\u51fa\u7248 |language=Japanese |isbn=978-4-7603-0138-6 |trans-title=To Young People Aspiring to Ballet: Together with Their Parents}}\n*{{cite book |last=\u30b5\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30a2\u8457 |first=\u30aa\u30ea\u30ac |title=\u30d0\u30ec\u30a8\u8aad\u672c |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k1WNkyeZBEMC&pg=PP1 |year=1980 |publisher=\u79d1\u5b66\u66f8\u9662 |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |isbn=978-4-7603-0137-9 |trans-title=Ballet Reader}}\n*{{cite book |last1=\u30b5\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30a2\u8457 |first1=\u30aa\u30ea\u30ac |last2=\u6e05\u6c34 |first2=\u5a01\u4e45(\u8a33) |title=\u308f\u305f\u3057\u306e\u30d0\u30ec\u30a8\u904d\u6b74 |year=1982 |publisher=\u971e\u30b1\u95a2\u51fa\u7248 |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=Ballet: My Life |oclc=33520162}}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Foreign-born Japanese]]\n*[[List of prima ballerinas]]\n* [[List of Russian ballet dancers]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Notes}}\n\n== References ==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{cite book |last=Ascher |first=Abraham |title=The Revolution of 1905: Russia in Disarray |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9J9Dt6EQHs8C&pg=PA93 |year=1994 |publisher=[[Stanford University Press]] |location=Stanford, California |isbn=978-0-8047-2327-5}}\n*{{cite journal |ref=harv |last1=\u041a\u0430\u0434\u0437\u0438 |first1=\u0410\u044f\u043a\u043e |last2=\u0428\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430 |first2=\u0410\u043b\u043b\u0430 |title=\u00ab\u0412\u044b \u0431\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u0446\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430...\u00bb: \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0431\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0435 \u044f\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043a\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0431\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0443 |journal=\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b [Saint-Petersburg Historical Journal] |date=2019 |issue=1 |pages=251\u2013264 |doi=10.24411/2311-603X-2019-00015 |trans-title='You Threw Flowers of Unfamiliar Art at Us...': Russian Ballerinas in the Service of Japanese Classical Ballet |publisher=\u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \"\u041d\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440-\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f\" |location=Saint Petersburg |language=Russian |issn=2311-603X}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Kenji |first1=Usui |editor1-last=Cohen |editor1-first=Selma Jeanne |title=International Encyclopedia of Dance |volume=3: Firebird, The-Kehlet, Niels |date=1998 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |location=New York, New York |isbn=0-19-512307-7 |pages=588-590 |url=https://archive.org/details/internationalenc0003unse/page/589/mode/1up |chapter=Japan: Ballet}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Koshiro |first1=Yukiko |title=Imperial Eclipse: Japan's Strategic Thinking about Continental Asia before August 1945 |date=2013 |publisher=[[Cornell University Press]] |location=Ithaca, New York |isbn=978-0-8014-5180-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AXBdviSYgE0C&pg=PA74}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-last=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 |editor1-first=\u041f.\u0410. |title=\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0442: \u042d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f |date=1997 |publisher=\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u044d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f, \u0421\u043e\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0438\u0435 |location=Moscow |isbn=5-85270-099-1 |language=Russian |chapter=\u0421\u0435\u043c\u0451\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u0438\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (\u0415\u0444\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447) |trans-title=Victor Alexandrovich (Efimovich) Semenov}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Monden |first1=Masafumi |title=Layers of the Ethereal: A Cultural Investigation of Beauty, Girlhood, and Ballet in Japanese Sh\u014djo Manga |journal=[[Fashion Theory]] |date=June 2014 |volume=18 |issue=3 |pages=251\u2013296 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/262584073_Layers_of_the_Ethereal_A_Cultural_Investigation_of_Beauty_Girlhood_and_Ballet_in_Japanese_Shojo_MangaI/link/55a6186a08ae00cf99c99bc1/download |doi=10.2752/175174114X13938552557808 |publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing |location=London |issn=1362-704X}}\n*{{cite conference |last1=\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0443\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0430 |first1=\u041b.\u041c |title=\u0427\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0431\u0430\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0438\u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0434\u0432\u0430\u0434\u0446\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430 \u0432 \u043f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0435-\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0435 |url=https://institutspb.ru/pdf/hearings/02-13_Petuhova.pdf |conference=\u0415\u0436\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0430\u044f \u041a\u043e\u043d\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0438\u044f \u041f\u043e \u041f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043c \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 21\u201322 January 1995  |publisher=Institute of Petersburg |accessdate=16 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200407135649/https://institutspb.ru/pdf/hearings/02-13_Petuhova.pdf |archivedate=7 April 2020 |location=Saint Petersburg, Russia |language=Russian |trans-title=Private Ballet Studios: Beginning of the Twentieth Century in Petersburg-Petrograd |date=22 January 1995}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Sato |first1=Toshiko |title=\u6226\u524d, \u6226\u5f8c\u3092\u65e5\u672c\u306b\u751f\u304d\u305f\u30ed\u30b7\u30a2\u306e\u821e\u59eb, \u30aa\u30ea\u30ac\u30fb\u30b5\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30a2 |journal=Choreologia |date=1996 |issue=19 |page=22 |doi=10.11235/buyougaku1978.1996.22 |publisher=Japanese Society for Dance Research |location=Tsukuba, Ibaraki |language=Japanese |trans-title=Olga Sapphire: A Russian Dance Princess Who Lived in Japan Before and After the War |issn=0911-4017}}\n*{{cite web |last1=\u95a2\u53e3 |first1=\u7d18\u4e00 |title=\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u30d0\u30ec\u30a8\u306e\u30d5\u30ed\u30f3\u30c6\u30a3\u30a2\u3001\u6a58\u79cb\u5b50\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066\u3000 |url=https://www.chacott-jp.com/news/column/others/detail003762.html |accessdate=21 April 2020 |website=Chacott.jp |publisher=Chacott Co., Ltd |date=1 September 2016 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200416191356/https://www.chacott-jp.com/news/column/others/detail003768.html |archivedate=16 April 2020 |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=About the Frontier of Japanese Ballet, Akiko Tachibana |url-status=live }}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|\u95a2\u53e3|2009b}} |last1=\u95a2\u53e3 |first1=\u7d18\u4e00 |title=\u300c\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u30d0\u30ec\u30a8\u306f\u3058\u307e\u308a\u7269\u8a9e\u300d\u30a8\u30ea\u30a2\u30ca\u30fb\u30d1\u30f4\u30ed\u30d0\u3068\u30aa\u30ea\u30ac\u30fb\u30b5\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30a2\u3000\u305d\u306e\u4e8c |url=https://www.chacott-jp.com/news/column/others/detail003768.html |accessdate=19 April 2020 |website=Chacott.jp |publisher=Chacott Co., Ltd |date=31 January 2009 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20200421195253/https://www.chacott-jp.com/news/column/others/detail003762.html |archivedate=21 April 2020 |location=Tokyo |language=Japanese |trans-title=\"Japanese Ballet Beginning Story\" Elena Pavlova and Olga Sapphire Part 2 |url-status=live }}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|\u95a2\u53e3|2009d}} |last1=\u95a2\u53e3 |first1=\u7d18\u4e00 |title=\u300c\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u30d0\u30ec\u30a8\u306f\u3058\u307e\u308a\u7269\u8a9e\u300d\u30a8\u30ea\u30a2\u30ca\u30fb\u30d1\u30f4\u30ed\u30d0\u3068\u30aa\u30ea\u30ac\u30fb\u30b5\u30d5\u30a1\u30a4\u30a2\u