6\u20131980):throughout", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Olga_Sapphire"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Smith (ice hockey)", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Tommy Smith\n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Centre]]\n| shoots = Left\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 6\n| weight_lb = 150\n| played_for = [[Pittsburgh Professionals]]<br/>[[Pittsburgh Lyceum]]<br/>[[Pittsburgh Bankers]]<br/> [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Hockey Club]]<br>Brantford Indians<br/>[[Galt Professionals]]<br/>Moncton Victorias<br/>[[Quebec Bulldogs]]<br/>[[Toronto Shamrocks]]<br/>[[Montreal Canadiens]]\n| league = [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1886|9|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_place = Ottawa, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite news |work=Ottawa Citizen |date=August 2, 1966 |title=Death Notices: Thomas J. Smith |p=32}}</ref>\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1966|8|1|1886|9|27}}\n| career_start = 1905\n| career_end = 1920\n| draft = \n| draft_year = \n| draft_team = \n| image = Tommy Smith of the Pittsburgh Professionals in 1907.jpg\n| caption = Tommy Smith in 1907 with the Pittsburgh Professionals\n| image_size = 230px\n| halloffame = 1973\n}}\n'''Thomas Joseph Smith''' (September 27, 1886 &ndash; August 1, 1966) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[professional]] [[ice hockey]] [[forward (ice hockey)|forward]], who played from 1905 until 1920 for 16 teams in his career. He was a member of two [[Stanley Cup]]-winning teams, the Ottawa Silver Seven of 1906 and the Quebec Bulldogs of 1913. His two brothers [[Alf Smith (ice hockey)|Alf Smith]] and [[Harry Smith (ice hockey, born 1883)|Harry Smith]] also played professional ice hockey.<ref name=\"pp\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19070306&id=GgsbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z0gEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2959,1390828 |title=Smith Family Famous in the Hockey World |work=The Pittsburgh Press |date=March 6, 1907 |p=14}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nSmith was born in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], to Mr. and Mrs. Henry Smith,<ref>{{cite news |work=Ottawa Citizen |title=Death Notices: Harry Smith |date=May 6, 1953 |p=34}}</ref> one of seven brothers who would play senior ice hockey.<ref name=\"pp\"/> Smith began playing senior hockey as an amateur with the Ottawa Emmetts from 1903 until 1905. He joined the [[Ottawa Victorias]] of the [[Federal Amateur Hockey League]] (FAHL) in 1905-06, and also played for the [[Stanley Cup]] champion [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Hockey Club]], aka the \"Silver Seven\" that same year, playing with his brothers Alf and Harry.\n\nHe moved to [[Pittsburgh]] to become a professional with the [[Pittsburgh Professionals]] in 1906, playing three seasons with the team before returning to Canada to join the Brantford Indians of the [[Ontario Professional Hockey League]] (OPHL). Smith played two seasons with Brantford. In 1910-11 he became a member of the [[Galt Professionals]] of the OPHL helping Galt win the OPHL championship. Along with most of the Galt team, he bolted to the [[Moncton Victorias]] the following season, helping Moncton win the Maritime championship. The Galt and Moncton teams Smith was a member of played consecutive Stanley Cup challenges, Galt against Ottawa in 1911 and Moncton against Quebec in 1912, both times unsuccessfully. Smith then joined the [[Quebec Bulldogs]]. After the 1913\u201314 season in Quebec, he was traded (twice) to [[Toronto Shamrocks]]. This caused a dispute with the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]]. At that time, the NHA and PCHA had an agreement whereby the PCHA teams could draft one player from three of the six teams of the NHA. He was traded away from Quebec, which was eligible to lose a player. He started play for Shamrocks, though he had been drafted by Victoria of the PCHA. It was found that the initial trade was not allowed, and Quebec re-traded him to Toronto during the season, disregarding the PCHA efforts to get him. During the 1914\u201315 season, he was traded back to Quebec, avoiding the PCHA draft again.\n\nWhile skating for the Ottawa Victorias in 1906, Smith led the FAHL with 12 goals (including eight goals in a game against [[Brockville, Ontario|Brockville]] on February 23, 1906). In future years, he was the leading goal-scorer in the OPHL (1908\u201309), the MPHA (1910\u201311) and the NHA (1913\u201314, 1914\u201315).\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"100\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"100\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP !! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]] !! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]] !! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]] !! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP !! G !! A !! Pts !! PIM\n|-\n| 1904\u201305\n| Ottawa Emmetts\n| [[Ottawa City Hockey League|OCHL]]\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1905\u201306 FAHL season|1905\u201306]]\n| [[Ottawa Victorias]]\n| [[Federal Amateur Hockey League|FAHL]]\n| 8 || 12 || 0 || 12 || \u2014\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[1905\u201306 ECAHA season|1905\u201306]]\n| [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]]\n| [[Eastern Canada Amateur Hockey Association|ECAHA]]\n| 3 || 6 || 0 || 6 || 12\n| 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 9\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1906\u201307 IPHL season|1906\u201307]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Professionals]]\n| [[International Professional Hockey League|IHL]]\n| 23 || 31 || 13 || 44 || 47\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[1907\u201308 WPHL season|1907\u201308]]\n| [[Pittsburgh Lyceum]]\n| [[Western Pennsylvania Hockey League|WPHL]]\n| 16 || 33 || 0 || 33 || \u2014\n| 1 || 2 || 0 || 2 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1908\u201309 OPHL season|1908\u201309]]\n| [[Brantford Indians]]\n| [[Ontario Professional Hockey League|OPHL]]\n| 13 || 40 || 0 || 40 || 30\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[1908\u201309 WPHL season|1908\u201309]]\n| Pittsburgh Lyceum\n| WPHL\n| 6 || 15 || 0 || 15 || \u2014\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 1908\u201309\n| [[Pittsburgh Bankers]]\n| WPHL\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| 7 || 3 || 1 || 4 || 14\n|-\n| 1908\u201309\n| [[Haileybury Comets]]\n| [[Timiskaming Professional Hockey League|TPHL]]\n| 1 || 3 || 0 || 3 || 2\n| 2 || 3 || 0 || 3 || 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1909\u201310 OPHL season|1909\u201310]]\n| Brantford Indians\n| OPHL\n| 2 || 1 || 0 || 1 || 3\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[1910\u201311 OPHL season|1910\u201311]]\n| [[Galt Professionals]]\n| OPHL\n| 18 || 22 || 0 || 22 || \u2014\n| 3 || 10 || 0 || 10 || 0\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1910\u201311 NHA season#Stanley Cup challenges|1910\u201311]]\n| Galt Professionals\n| [[Stanley Cup|St-Cup]]\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| 1 || 1 || 0 || 1 || \u2014\n|-\n| 1911\u201312\n| Moncton Victorias\n| [[Maritime Professional Hockey League|MPHL]]\n| 71 || 27 || 25 || 52 || 14\n| 9 || 4 || 3 || 7 || 2\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1911\u201312 NHA season#Stanley Cup challenges|1911\u201312]]\n| Moncton Victorias\n| St-Cup\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| 2 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 3\n|-\n| [[1912\u201313 NHA season|1912\u201313]]\n| [[Quebec Bulldogs]]\n| [[National Hockey Association|NHA]]\n| 18 || 39 || 0 || 39 || 30\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1912\u201313 NHA season#Stanley Cup challenges|1912\u201313]]\n| Quebec Bulldogs\n| St-Cup\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| 2 || 4 || 0 || 4 || 0\n|-\n| [[1913\u201314 NHA season|1913\u201314]]\n| Quebec Bulldogs\n| NHA\n| 20 || 39 || 6 || 45 || 35\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1914\u201315 NHA season|1914\u201315]]\n| [[Toronto Shamrocks]]\n| NHA\n| 10 || 17 || 2 || 19 || 14\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| 1914\u201315\n| Quebec Bulldogs\n| NHA\n| 9 || 23 || 2 || 25 || 29\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1915\u201316 NHA season|1915\u201316]]\n| Quebec Bulldogs\n| NHA\n| 22 || 16 || 3 || 19 || 30\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[1916\u201317 NHA season|1916\u201317]]\n| [[Montreal Canadiens]]\n| NHA\n| 14 || 7 || 4 || 11 || 32\n| 2 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 11\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1917 Stanley Cup Final|1916\u201317]]\n| Montreal Canadiens\n| St-Cup\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| 4 || 2 || 0 || 2 || 3\n|-\n| 1917\u201318\n| Ottawa Transport\n| OCHL\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| 1918\u201319\n| Glace Bay Miners\n| CBSHL\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[1919\u201320 NHL season|1919\u201320]]\n| [[Quebec Bulldogs]]\n| [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| 10 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 11\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\"|NHL totals\n! 93 !! 141 !! 17 !! 158 !! 170\n! 2 !! 2 !! 0 !! 2 !! 11\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\"|NHL totals\n! 10 !! 0 !! 1 !! 1 !! 11\n! \u2014 !! \u2014 !! \u2014 !! \u2014 !! \u2014\n|}\n\n==Awards and achievements==\n* 1906 \u2013 Member of Stanley Cup champion Ottawa Silver Seven\n* 1913 \u2013 [[Stanley Cup]] Champion with the [[Quebec Bulldogs]]\n* 1973 \u2013 Inducted into the [[Hockey Hall of Fame]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{icehockeystats|legendsm=P197303}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1886 births]]\n[[Category:1966 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian ice hockey centres]]\n[[Category:Hockey Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Ice hockey people from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Montreal Canadiens (NHA) players]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Senators (original) players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Bankers players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Lyceum (ice hockey) players]]\n[[Category:Pittsburgh Professionals players]]\n[[Category:Quebec Bulldogs (NHA) players]]\n[[Category:Quebec Bulldogs players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Stanley Cup champions]]\n[[Category:Toronto Shamrocks players]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Tommy Smith\n| position = [[Centre (ice hockey)|Centre]]\n| shoots = Left\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 6\n| weight_lb = 150\n| played_for = [[Pittsburgh Professionals]]<br/>[[Pittsburgh Lyceum]]<br/>[[Pittsburgh Bankers]]<br/> [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Hockey Club]]<br>Brantford Indians<br/>[[Galt Professionals]]<br/>Moncton Victorias<br/>[[Quebec Bulldogs]]<br/>[[Toronto Shamrocks]]<br/>[[Montreal Canadiens]]\n| league = [[National Hockey League|NHL]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1886|9|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada\n| death_place = Ottawa, Ontario, Canada<ref>{{cite news |work=Ottawa Citizen |date=August 2, 1966 |title=Death Notices: Thomas J. Smith |p=32}}</ref>\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1966|8|1|1886|9|27}}\n| career_start = 1905\n| career_end = 1920\n| draft = \n| draft_year = \n| draft_team = \n| image = Tommy Smith of the Pittsburgh Professionals in 1907.jpg\n| caption = Tommy Smith in 1907 with the Pittsburgh Professionals\n| image_size = 230px\n| halloffame = 1973\n}}\n'''Thomas Joseph Smith''' (September 27, 1886 &ndash; August 1, 1966) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] [[professional]] [[ice hockey]] [[forward (ice hockey)|forward]], who played from 1905 until 1920 for 16 teams in his career. He was a member of two [[Stanley Cup]]-winning teams, the Ottawa Silver Seven of 1906 and the Quebec Bulldogs of 1913. His two brothers [[Alf Smith (ice hockey)|Alf Smith]] and [[Harry Smith (ice hockey, born 1883)|Harry Smith]] also played professional ice hockey.<ref name=\"pp\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19070306&id=GgsbAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z0gEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2959,1390828 |title=Smith Family Famous in the Hockey World |work=The Pittsburgh Press |date=March 6, 1907 |p=14}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nSmith was born in [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], to Mr. and Mrs. Henry Smith,<ref>{{cite news |work=Ottawa Citizen |title=Death Notices: Harry Smith |date=May 6, 1953 |p=34}}</ref> one of seven brothers who would play senior ice hockey.<ref name=\"pp\"/> Smith began playing senior hockey as an amateur with the Ottawa Emmetts from 1903 until 1905. He joined the [[Ottawa Victorias]] of the [[Federal Amateur Hockey League]] (FAHL) in 1905-06, and also played for the [[Stanley Cup]] champion [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Hockey Club]], aka the \"Silver Seven\" that same year, playing with his brothers Alf and Harry.\n\nHe moved to [[Pittsburgh]] to become a professional with the [[Pittsburgh Professionals]] in 1906, playing three seasons with the team before returning to Canada to join the Brantford Indians of the [[Ontario Professional Hockey League]] (OPHL). Smith played two seasons with Brantford. In 1910-11 he became a member of the [[Galt Professionals]] of the OPHL helping Galt win the OPHL championship. Along with most of the Galt team, he bolted to the [[Moncton Victorias]] the following season, helping Moncton win the Maritime championship. The Galt and Moncton teams Smith was a member of played consecutive Stanley Cup challenges, Galt against Ottawa in 1911 and Moncton against Quebec in 1912, both times unsuccessfully. Smith then joined the [[Quebec Bulldogs]]. After the 1913\u201314 season in Quebec, he was traded (twice) to [[Toronto Shamrocks]]. This caused a dispute with the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]]. At that time, the NHA and PCHA had an agreement whereby the PCHA teams could draft one player from three of the six teams of the NHA. He was traded away from Quebec, which was eligible to lose a player. He started play for Shamrocks, though he had been drafted by Victoria of the PCHA. It was found that the initial trade was not allowed, and Quebec re-traded him to Toronto during the season, disregarding the PCHA efforts to get him. During the 1914\u201315 season, he was traded back to Quebec, avoiding the PCHA draft again.\n\nWhile skating for the Ottawa Victorias in 1906, Smith led the FAHL with 12 goals (including eight goals in a game against [[Brockville, Ontario|Brockville]] on February 23, 1906). In future years, he was the leading goal-scorer in the OPHL (1908\u201309), the MPHA (1910\u201311) and the NHA (1913\u201314, 1914\u201315).\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! rowspan=\"100\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Regular season]]\n! rowspan=\"100\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\"|\n! colspan=\"5\"|[[Playoffs]]\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP !! [[Goal (ice hockey)|G]] !! [[Assist (ice hockey)|A]] !! [[Point (ice hockey)|Pts]] !! [[Penalty (ice hockey)|PIM]]\n! GP !! G !! A !! Pts !! PIM\n|-\n| 1904\u201305\n| Ottawa Emmetts\n| OCHL\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|- bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[1905\u201306 FAHL season|1905\u201306]]\n| [[Ottawa Victorias]]\n| [[Federal Amateur Hockey League|FAHL]]\n| 8 || 12 || 0 || 12 || \u2014\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n| [[1905\u201306 ECAHA season|1905\u201306]]\n| [[Ottawa Senators (original)|Ottawa Senators]]\n| [[Eastern Canada Amateur Hockey Association|ECAHA]]\n| 3 || 6 || 0 || 6 || 12\n| 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 9\n|-